49:
50:## Types
51:
52:Package consumers should import public types and utilities from the root module, `civ-engine`. Source file comments below identify where each type is owned.
53:
54:### `EntityId`
55:
56:```typescript
57:// src/types.ts
58:type EntityId = number;
59:```
60:
61:Numeric identifier for entities. IDs are recycled via a free-list after destruction. Two entities may share the same ID across different lifetimes but never simultaneously.
62:
63:### `EntityRef`
64:
65:```typescript
66:// src/types.ts
67:interface EntityRef {
68:  id: EntityId;
69:  generation: number;
70:}
71:```
72:
73:Generation-aware entity reference. Use this for external commands and clients that need to detect stale entity IDs after destruction and recycling.
74:
75:### `Position`
76:
77:```typescript
78:// src/types.ts
79:interface Position {
80:  x: number;
81:  y: number;
82:}
83:```
84:
85:Standard 2D position interface used for spatial grid synchronization. The component key for spatial tracking is configurable via `WorldConfig.positionKey` (default `'position'`).
86:
87:### `InstrumentationProfile`
88:
89:```typescript
90:// src/types.ts
91:type InstrumentationProfile = 'full' | 'minimal' | 'release';
92:```
93:
94:Controls how much implicit runtime instrumentation the engine keeps on the hot path.
95:
96:- `full` keeps the normal development behavior. `step()` records detailed per-tick metrics and `submit()` preserves the compatibility wrapper over `submitWithResult()`.
97:- `minimal` is the QA/staging profile. `step()` records coarse per-tick metrics such as counts and total duration, but skips detailed phase timings and per-system timing entries.
98:- `release` removes avoidable observation work from the implicit `step()` and `submit()` paths. Explicit AI/debug APIs such as `stepWithResult()` and `submitWithResult()` still return structured results when you call them.
99:
100:### `WorldConfig`
101:
102:```typescript
103:// src/types.ts
104:interface WorldConfig {
105:  gridWidth: number;       // Width of the spatial grid (required)
106:  gridHeight: number;      // Height of the spatial grid (required)
107:  tps: number;             // Ticks per second for real-time loop (required)
108:  positionKey?: string;    // Component key used for spatial sync (default: 'position')
109:  maxTicksPerFrame?: number; // Spiral-of-death cap (default: 4)
110:  seed?: number | string;  // Deterministic RNG seed
111:  instrumentationProfile?: InstrumentationProfile; // Implicit instrumentation level (default: 'full')
112:}
113:```
114:
115:### `System`
116:
117:```typescript
118:// src/world.ts
119:type System<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState> = (
120:  world: World<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>,
121:) => void;
122:```
123:
124:A system is a pure function that receives the `World` and runs game logic. Systems execute by phase, preserving registration order within each phase. Bare function registrations default to the `update` phase. All four generics default to permissive types so existing 2-generic call sites continue to compile; threading `TComponents` and `TState` through gives compile-time-typed `world.getComponent` / `world.getState` access inside the callback body.
125:
126:### `SystemRegistration`
127:
128:```typescript
129:// src/world.ts
130:interface SystemRegistration<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState> {
131:  name?: string;
132:  phase?: 'input' | 'preUpdate' | 'update' | 'postUpdate' | 'output';
133:  before?: string[];
134:  after?: string[];
135:  interval?: number;
136:  intervalOffset?: number;
137:  execute: System<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>;
138:}
139:```
140:
141:Optional system registration object for naming systems and assigning a lifecycle phase. The `before` and `after` fields declare ordering constraints between named systems within the same phase (see [System Ordering Constraints](#registersystemfnorconfig)).
142:
143:`interval` (default `1`) gates how often the system runs. The system fires only when `(executingTick - 1) % interval === intervalOffset`, where `executingTick` is the tick number being processed (equal to `world.tick + 1` while the system is running, or equivalently the value of `world.tick` after `step()` returns successfully). With `interval: 4` and `intervalOffset: 0`, the system runs at ticks 1, 5, 9, 13 — i.e., it fires on the first tick and then every 4 ticks, which matches the legacy `if (world.tick % 4 !== 0) return;` pattern.
144:
145:`intervalOffset` (default `0`, must satisfy `0 <= intervalOffset < interval`) shifts the cadence within the cycle. `interval: 4, intervalOffset: 1` fires at ticks 2, 6, 10. Three systems with `interval: 3` and offsets `0`/`1`/`2` partition every tick into a stable round-robin.
146:
147:Use intervals to throttle expensive subsystems (slow propagation, periodic AI re-planning, weather updates) without changing each system's logic. Skipped systems do not invoke their `execute` body and do not push a per-system entry into `metrics.systems`; the per-tick total in `metrics.durationMs.systems` still includes the cheap modulo check across all registered systems, so the savings come from the body, not from the dispatch. **Failed ticks consume a cadence slot:** if the executing tick fails, any periodic system whose modulo aligned with that tick simply does not fire — the engine does not retry on the next successful tick.
148:
149:Validation throws at registration if `interval` is not a safe integer (`Number.isSafeInteger`) >= 1, or if `intervalOffset` is not a safe integer in `[0, interval)`. Bounding `interval` to safe-integer range avoids non-deterministic modulo results past `2^53`.
150:
151:### `LooseSystem`
152:
153:```typescript
154:// src/world.ts
155:type LooseSystem = (world: World<any, any, any, any>) => void;
156:```
157:
158:A system typed against a bare `World` that does not need explicit casts when registered into a generically typed world. Useful for utility systems that do not depend on specific event/command/component/state maps.
159:
160:### `LooseSystemRegistration`
161:
162:```typescript
163:// src/world.ts
164:interface LooseSystemRegistration {
165:  name?: string;
166:  phase?: 'input' | 'preUpdate' | 'update' | 'postUpdate' | 'output';
167:  before?: string[];
168:  after?: string[];
169:  interval?: number;
170:  intervalOffset?: number;
171:  execute: LooseSystem;
172:}
173:```
174:
175:Same shape as `SystemRegistration` but uses `LooseSystem` instead. `interval` and `intervalOffset` carry the same semantics as on `SystemRegistration`.
176:
177:### `ComponentRegistry`
178:
179:```typescript
180:// src/types.ts
181:type ComponentRegistry = Record<string, unknown>;
182:```
183:
184:Third type parameter to `World<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>`. When specified, component methods (`addComponent`, `getComponent`, `setComponent`, `patchComponent`, `removeComponent`, `query`) infer value types from the registry keys, eliminating manual generic annotations. The fourth `TState` generic plays the analogous role for `world.setState` / `world.getState`. Both generics thread through `System`, `SystemRegistration`, `registerSystem`, `registerValidator`, `registerHandler`, `onDestroy`, and `World.deserialize` so typed access works inside callback bodies.
185:
186:### `WorldMetrics`
187:
188:```typescript
189:// src/world.ts
190:interface WorldMetrics {
191:  tick: number;
192:  entityCount: number;
193:  componentStoreCount: number;
194:  simulation: { tps: number; tickBudgetMs: number };
195:  commandStats: { pendingBeforeTick: number; processed: number };
196:  systems: Array<{ name: string; phase: SystemPhase; durationMs: number }>;
197:  query: { calls: number; cacheHits: number; cacheMisses: number; results: number };
198:  spatial: { explicitSyncs: number };
