322:
323:Structured runtime failure for one tick. Returned by `world.stepWithResult()`, emitted through `world.onTickFailure()`, exposed through `world.getLastTickFailure()`, and forwarded by `ClientAdapter`.
324:
325:### `WorldStepResult`
326:
327:```typescript
328:// src/world.ts
329:interface WorldStepResult {
330:  schemaVersion: number;
331:  ok: boolean;
332:  tick: number;
333:  failure: TickFailure | null;
334:}
335:```
336:
337:Structured result returned by `world.stepWithResult()`.
338:
339:### `WorldTickFailureError`
340:
341:```typescript
342:// src/world.ts
343:class WorldTickFailureError extends Error {
344:  readonly failure: TickFailure;
345:}
346:```
347:
348:Thrown by `world.step()` when a tick fails. Also thrown by `world.step()` (and surfaced as a `world_poisoned` failure result by `world.stepWithResult()`) for any subsequent step until `world.recover()` is called — see Tick failure semantics.
349:
350:### Tick failure semantics
351:
352:A failure in any tick phase (commands, systems, resources, diff, listeners) marks the world as **poisoned**:
353:
354:- `world.isPoisoned(): boolean` returns `true` until the next call to `recover()`.
355:- While poisoned, `world.step()` throws `WorldTickFailureError` and `world.stepWithResult()` returns a `WorldStepResult` with `failure.code === 'world_poisoned'`. The original failure that caused the poison is preserved on the result for diagnostics.
356:- `world.recover(): void` clears the poison flag and the cached `lastTickFailure`/`currentDiff`/`currentMetrics`. After `recover()`, the next `step()` runs normally.
357:
358:Failed ticks consume a tick number. If a tick fails at would-be tick `N+1`, `world.tick` advances to `N+1`; the next successful tick after `recover()` is `N+2`. This guarantees that failed-tick events and successful-tick events never share a `tick` value, so consumers can correlate by tick number unambiguously.
359:
360:When a command handler throws (or its handler is missing), every command queued for that tick that has not yet executed is emitted as a `commandExecuted: false` event with `code: 'tick_aborted_before_handler'`, and the dropped commands' `submissionSequence`s are recorded on `failure.details.droppedCommands`. The queue is not re-populated — these commands are dropped, not retried.
361:
362:### `WorldSnapshot`
363:
364:```typescript
365:// src/serializer.ts
366:interface WorldSnapshot {
367:  version: 5;
368:  config: WorldConfig; // includes maxTicksPerFrame and instrumentationProfile when non-default
369:  tick: number;
370:  entities: {
371:    generations: number[];
372:    alive: boolean[];
373:    freeList: number[];
374:  };
375:  components: Record<string, Array<[EntityId, unknown]>>;
376:  componentOptions?: Record<string, ComponentStoreOptions>; // diffMode per component
377:  resources: ResourceStoreState;
378:  rng: RandomState;
379:  state: Record<string, unknown>;
380:  tags: Record<number, string[]>;
381:  metadata: Record<number, Record<string, string | number>>;
382:}
383:```
384:
385:JSON-serializable snapshot of the entire world state, deep-cloned at both serialize and deserialize boundaries so callers cannot mutate live engine state through it. Used by `serialize()` and `World.deserialize()`. Version 5 adds `componentOptions` (per-component `diffMode` round-trip) and serializes `WorldConfig.maxTicksPerFrame` / `WorldConfig.instrumentationProfile` when non-default. Version 4 added world-level state, entity tags, and entity metadata. Version 3 includes deterministic RNG state so a saved simulation resumes the same random sequence. Version 2 includes resource registrations, pools, rates, transfers, and the next transfer ID. Versions 1–4 are still accepted by `World.deserialize()` for backward compatibility — older snapshots without `componentOptions` deserialize each component store with default options. Systems, validators, handlers, and event listeners are not included (they are functions, not data). Pre-0.5.0 snapshots may include `config.detectInPlacePositionMutations` and `componentOptions[*].detectInPlaceMutations`; both are silently ignored on read in 0.5.0+.
