998:### `GameEvent<TEventMap>`
999:
1000:```typescript
1001:// src/client-adapter.ts
1002:type GameEvent<TEventMap> = {
1003:  type: keyof TEventMap;
1004:  data: TEventMap[keyof TEventMap];
1005:};
1006:```
1007:
1008:### `ServerMessage<TEventMap>`
1009:
1010:```typescript
1011:// src/client-adapter.ts
1012:type ServerMessage<TEventMap> =
1013:  | { protocolVersion: number; type: 'snapshot'; data: WorldSnapshot }
1014:  | { protocolVersion: number; type: 'tick'; data: { diff: TickDiff; events: GameEvent<TEventMap>[] } }
1015:  | {
1016:      protocolVersion: number;
1017:      type: 'commandAccepted';
1018:      data: { id: string; commandType: string; code: 'accepted'; message: string };
1019:    }
1020:  | {
1021:      protocolVersion: number;
1022:      type: 'commandRejected';
1023:      data: {
1024:        id: string;
1025:        commandType: string | null;
1026:        code: string;
1027:        message: string;
1028:        details: JsonValue | null;
1029:        validatorIndex: number | null;
1030:      };
1031:    }
1032:  | {
1033:      protocolVersion: number;
1034:      type: 'commandExecuted';
1035:      data: {
1036:        id: string;
1037:        commandType: string;
1038:        submissionSequence: number | null;
1039:        code: string;
1040:        message: string;
1041:        details: JsonValue | null;
1042:        tick: number;
1043:      };
1044:    }
1045:  | {
1046:      protocolVersion: number;
1047:      type: 'commandFailed';
1048:      data: {
1049:        id: string;
1050:        commandType: string;
1051:        submissionSequence: number | null;
1052:        code: string;
1053:        message: string;
1054:        details: JsonValue | null;
1055:        tick: number;
1056:      };
1057:    }
1058:  | {
1059:      protocolVersion: number;
1060:      type: 'tickFailed';
1061:      data: TickFailure;
1062:    };
1063:```
1064:
1065:Messages sent from server to client:
1066:
1067:| Type | When sent | Payload |
1068:|---|---|---|
1069:| `snapshot` | On `connect()` or `requestSnapshot` | `protocolVersion` + full `WorldSnapshot` |
1070:| `tick` | After each `step()` while connected | `protocolVersion` + `TickDiff` + events from the tick |
1071:| `commandAccepted` | When a submitted command passed validation and was queued | `protocolVersion` + command ID + command type + accepted message |
1072:| `commandRejected` | When the adapter rejects a malformed, unhandled, or validation-failed command | `protocolVersion` + command ID + command type + stable code/message/details |
1073:| `commandExecuted` | When a queued client command completes during a tick | `protocolVersion` + command ID + command type + submission sequence + execution code/message/details + tick |
1074:| `commandFailed` | When a queued client command fails during a tick | `protocolVersion` + command ID + command type + submission sequence + failure code/message/details + tick |
1075:| `tickFailed` | When the world reports a structured tick failure | `protocolVersion` + `TickFailure` |
1076:
1077:### `ClientMessage<TCommandMap>`
1078:
1079:```typescript
1080:// src/client-adapter.ts
1081:type ClientMessage<TCommandMap> =
1082:  | { protocolVersion?: number; type: 'command'; data: { id: string; commandType: keyof TCommandMap; payload: TCommandMap[keyof TCommandMap] } }
1083:  | { protocolVersion?: number; type: 'requestSnapshot' };
1084:```
1085:
1086:Messages sent from client to server:
1087:
1088:| Type | Purpose | Payload |
1089:|---|---|---|
1090:| `command` | Submit a game command | Optional `protocolVersion`, command ID, type, and payload |
1091:| `requestSnapshot` | Request a full state resync | Optional `protocolVersion` |
1092:
1093:---
1094:
1095:## World
1096:
1097:`World<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents>` is the top-level API and the only public entry point. All subsystems (entity manager, component stores, spatial grid, game loop, event bus, command queue, resource store) are owned as private fields.
1098:
1099:```typescript
1100:import { World } from 'civ-engine';
1101:```
1102:
1103:### Type Parameters
1104:
1105:| Parameter | Constraint | Default | Description |
1106:|---|---|---|---|
1107:| `TEventMap` | `Record<keyof TEventMap, unknown>` | `Record<string, never>` | Map of event type names to event data types |
1108:| `TCommandMap` | `Record<keyof TCommandMap, unknown>` | `Record<string, never>` | Map of command type names to command data types |
1109:| `TComponents` | `ComponentRegistry` | `Record<string, unknown>` | Optional component registry. When specified, component methods infer value types from registry keys |
1110:
1111:### Constructor
1112:
1113:```typescript
1114:new World<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents>(config: WorldConfig)
1115:```
1116:
1117:Creates a new world with the specified grid dimensions, tick rate, and optional configuration.
1118:
1119:**Parameters:**
1120:
1121:| Name | Type | Required | Description |
1122:|---|---|---|---|
1123:| `config.gridWidth` | `number` | Yes | Width of the spatial grid in cells |
1124:| `config.gridHeight` | `number` | Yes | Height of the spatial grid in cells |
1125:| `config.tps` | `number` | Yes | Ticks per second for the real-time loop |
1126:| `config.positionKey` | `string` | No | Component key used for spatial grid sync (default: `'position'`) |
1127:| `config.maxTicksPerFrame` | `number` | No | Maximum ticks processed per real-time frame before discarding accumulated time (default: `4`) |
1128:| `config.seed` | `number \| string` | No | Seed for deterministic `world.random()` sequences |
1129:
1130:**Example:**
1131:
1132:```typescript
1133:const world = new World({ gridWidth: 64, gridHeight: 64, tps: 10 });
1134:```
1135:
1136:### Entity Management
1137:
1138:#### `createEntity()`
1139:
1140:```typescript
1141:createEntity(): EntityId
1142:```
1143:
1144:Creates a new entity and returns its ID. IDs are recycled from previously destroyed entities via a free-list. Entity IDs start at `0` and increment.
1145:
1146:**Returns:** `EntityId` — the new entity's numeric ID.
1147:
1148:```typescript
1149:const unit = world.createEntity(); // 0
1150:const building = world.createEntity(); // 1
1151:```
1152:
1153:#### `destroyEntity(id)`
1154:
1155:```typescript
1156:destroyEntity(id: EntityId): void
1157:```
1158:
1159:Immediately destroys an entity. Performs full cleanup in this order:
1160:
1161:1. Fires all `onDestroy` callbacks (with components still attached)
1162:2. Removes entity from the spatial grid using its last-synced position
1163:3. Removes all components from all stores
1164:4. Removes all resource pools, production rates, consumption rates, and transfers
1165:5. Removes all tags and metadata associated with the entity
1166:6. Marks the entity as dead in the entity manager (ID becomes available for recycling)
1167:
1168:**No-op** if the entity is already dead.
1169:
1170:```typescript
1171:world.destroyEntity(unit);
1172:world.isAlive(unit); // false
1173:```
1174:
1175:#### `isAlive(id)`
1176:
1177:```typescript
1178:isAlive(id: EntityId): boolean
1179:```
1180:
1181:Returns `true` if the entity exists and has not been destroyed. Returns `false` for IDs that were never created or have been destroyed.
1182:
1183:```typescript
1184:const e = world.createEntity();
1185:world.isAlive(e);    // true
1186:world.destroyEntity(e);
1187:world.isAlive(e);    // false
1188:world.isAlive(999);  // false
1189:```
1190:
1191:#### `getEntityRef(id)`
1192:
1193:```typescript
1194:getEntityRef(id: EntityId): EntityRef | null
1195:```
1196:
1197:Returns a generation-aware reference for a live entity, or `null` if the entity is not alive.
1198:
1199:#### `isCurrent(ref)`
1200:
1201:```typescript
1202:isCurrent(ref: EntityRef): boolean
1203:```
1204:
1205:Returns `true` only if the referenced entity ID is alive and still has the same generation.
1206:
1207:#### `getAliveEntities()`
1208:
1209:```typescript
1210:getAliveEntities(): IterableIterator<EntityId>
1211:```
1212:
1213:Yields every live entity id in ascending order. Cheaper than reading `world.serialize().entities.alive` when you only need to iterate the set (no JSON-compat walk on component data). Useful for renderer adapters connecting mid-session.
1214:
1215:#### `getEntityGeneration(id)`
1216:
1217:```typescript
1218:getEntityGeneration(id: EntityId): number
1219:```
1220:
1221:Returns the current generation counter for the given entity id. Combined with `getAliveEntities()` lets a caller build `EntityRef` objects without going through `getEntityRef` per entity.
1222:
1223:### Components
1224:
1225:#### `registerComponent<T>(key, options?)`
1226:
1227:```typescript
1228:registerComponent<T>(key: string, options?: ComponentOptions): void
1229:
1230:interface ComponentOptions {
1231:  diffMode?: 'strict' | 'semantic';
1232:}
1233:```
1234:
1235:Registers a component type by string key. Must be called before using `addComponent`, `getComponent`, `removeComponent`, or `query` with this key.
1236:
1237:`options.diffMode` controls how component writes participate in `TickDiff`:
1238:- `'strict'` (default) — every `addComponent` / `setComponent` call marks the entity dirty, even if the new value is identical to the prior value. Preserves per-write audit semantics.
1239:- `'semantic'` — writes are fingerprinted against the baseline from the last tick; identical rewrites do not mark the entity dirty. Use this for components whose sync systems rewrite unchanged values every tick (e.g. `position`, `transform`) to keep `TickDiff` liveness signals high.
1240:
1241:In-place mutations of component objects (`world.getComponent(id, 'foo').x = 5`) are NOT tracked by the diff system. Game code must call `setComponent`/`addComponent`/`patchComponent` for changes to land in the diff. The dirty set is updated only by the explicit write APIs.
1242:
1243:`options.diffMode` is round-tripped in v5 snapshots so save/load preserves component-store behavior.
1244:
1245:**Throws:** `Error` if a component with this key is already registered.
1246:
1247:```typescript
1248:interface Health { hp: number; maxHp: number }
1249:world.registerComponent<Health>('health');
1250:
1251:interface Transform { x: number; y: number }
1252:world.registerComponent<Transform>('transform', { diffMode: 'semantic' });
1253:```
1254:
1255:#### `addComponent<T>(entity, key, data)`
1256:
1257:```typescript
1258:addComponent<T>(entity: EntityId, key: string, data: T): void
1259:```
1260:
1261:Attaches a component to an entity. If the entity already has this component, it is overwritten.
1262:
1263:**Throws:** `Error` if the entity is not alive, the component key is not registered, or the data is not JSON-compatible.
1264:
1265:```typescript
1266:world.addComponent(unit, 'health', { hp: 100, maxHp: 100 });
1267:```
1268:
1269:`addComponent` is kept as a compatibility alias for `setComponent`.
1270:
1271:#### `setComponent<T>(entity, key, data)`
1272:
1273:```typescript
1274:setComponent<T>(entity: EntityId, key: string, data: T): void
1275:```
1276:
1277:Sets or replaces a component, marks it dirty for diffs, and updates the spatial grid immediately when `key` is the world's `positionKey`.
1278:
1279:#### `patchComponent<T>(entity, key, fn)`
1280:
1281:```typescript
1282:patchComponent<T>(
1283:  entity: EntityId,
1284:  key: string,
1285:  patch: (data: T) => T | void,
1286:): T
1287:```
1288:
1289:Reads an existing component, lets the callback mutate it or return a replacement, then marks it dirty.
1290:
1291:#### `setPosition(entity, position, key?)`
1292:
1293:```typescript
1294:setPosition(entity: EntityId, position: Position, key?: string): void
1295:```
1296:
1297:Sets position data and updates the spatial grid immediately when the key is the world's `positionKey`.
1298:
1299:#### `getComponent<T>(entity, key)`
1300:
1301:```typescript
1302:getComponent<T>(entity: EntityId, key: string): T | undefined
1303:```
1304:
1305:Returns the component data for the given entity and key, or `undefined` if the entity does not have this component. The returned object is a direct reference, so mutations are reflected immediately. Direct mutations are detected for diffs, but `setComponent()` and `patchComponent()` are the preferred write APIs for clearer intent and immediate position/grid synchronization.
1306:
1307:```typescript
1308:const hp = world.getComponent<Health>(unit, 'health');
1309:if (hp) {
1310:  hp.hp -= 10; // mutate in-place
1311:}
1312:```
1313:
1314:#### `getComponents<T>(entity, keys)`
1315:
1316:```typescript
1317:getComponents<T extends unknown[]>(entity: EntityId, keys: string[]): ComponentTuple<T>
1318:```
1319:
1320:Batch-reads multiple components for a single entity. Returns a tuple where each element is the component data or `undefined`. More concise than multiple `getComponent` calls.
1321:
1322:**Type:** `ComponentTuple<T>` is `{ [K in keyof T]: T[K] | undefined }`.
1323:
1324:```typescript
1325:const [pos, hp, vel] = world.getComponents<[Position, Health, Velocity]>(
1326:  unit,
1327:  ['position', 'health', 'velocity'],
1328:);
1329:// pos: Position | undefined
1330:// hp: Health | undefined
1331:// vel: Velocity | undefined
1332:```
1333:
1334:#### `removeComponent(entity, key)`
1335:
1336:```typescript
1337:removeComponent(entity: EntityId, key: string): void
1338:```
1339:
1340:Detaches a component from an entity. No-op if the entity doesn't have this component.
1341:
1342:```typescript
1343:world.removeComponent(unit, 'velocity');
1344:```
1345:
1346:#### `query(...keys)`
1347:
1348:```typescript
1349:*query(...keys: string[]): IterableIterator<EntityId>
1350:```
1351:
1352:Returns an iterator over all entity IDs that have **every** specified component. Query membership is cached by component signature and updated as components are added, removed, or entities are destroyed.
1353:
1354:**Throws:** `Error` if any component key is not registered.
1355:
1356:Returns immediately (yields nothing) if `keys` is empty.
1357:
1358:```typescript
1359:// Iterate
1360:for (const id of world.query('position', 'health')) {
1361:  // id has both 'position' and 'health'
1362:}
1363:
1364:// Collect to array
1365:const soldiers = [...world.query('position', 'health', 'attack')];
1366:```
1367:
1368:### Systems & Simulation
1369:
