1380:```
1381:
1382:Adds a system to the pipeline. Bare functions run in the `update` phase. Registration objects can name systems for metrics and assign a phase. Systems run in this phase order: `input`, `preUpdate`, `update`, `postUpdate`, `output`; registration order is preserved within each phase.
1383:
1384:The overload accepting `LooseSystem | LooseSystemRegistration` allows systems typed against `World<any, any>` to be registered without casts, which is useful for generic utility systems.
1385:
1386:**Ordering constraints:** `SystemRegistration` (and `LooseSystemRegistration`) support optional `before` and `after` arrays to declare ordering dependencies between named systems within the same phase. Constraints are resolved via topological sort.
1387:
1388:| Field | Type | Description |
1389:|---|---|---|
1390:| `before` | `string[]` | Run this system before the named systems |
1391:| `after` | `string[]` | Run this system after the named systems |
1392:| `interval` | `number` | Run only on ticks where `(executingTick - 1) % interval === intervalOffset` (default `1`) |
1393:| `intervalOffset` | `number` | Cycle offset within `[0, interval)` (default `0`); shifts which absolute tick number triggers the system within the modulo cycle |
1394:
1395:**Throws:**
1396:- `Error` if a constraint creates a cycle within a phase
1397:- `Error` if a constraint references a system in a different phase
1398:- `Error` if a constraint references a non-existent system name
1399:- `Error` if `interval` is not a safe integer >= 1
1400:- `Error` if `intervalOffset` is not a safe integer in `[0, interval)`
1401:
1402:```typescript
1403:function movementSystem(w: World): void {
1404:  for (const id of w.query('position', 'velocity')) {
1405:    const pos = w.getComponent<Position>(id, 'position')!;
1406:    const vel = w.getComponent<Velocity>(id, 'velocity')!;
1407:    w.setPosition(id, { x: pos.x + vel.dx, y: pos.y + vel.dy });
1408:  }
1409:}
1410:
1411:world.registerSystem(movementSystem);
1412:world.registerSystem({
1413:  name: 'Combat',
1414:  phase: 'postUpdate',
1415:  execute: combatSystem,
1416:});
1417:
1418:// Ordering: Movement runs before Combat within the same phase
1419:world.registerSystem({
1420:  name: 'Movement',
1421:  phase: 'update',
1422:  before: ['Collision'],
1423:  execute: movementSystem,
1424:});
1425:world.registerSystem({
1426:  name: 'Collision',
1427:  phase: 'update',
1428:  after: ['Movement'],
1429:  execute: collisionSystem,
1430:});
1431:
1432:// Cadence: heavy weather sim runs every 12 ticks (fires at tick 1, 13, 25, ...)
1433:world.registerSystem({
1434:  name: 'Weather',
1435:  phase: 'update',
1436:  interval: 12,
1437:  execute: weatherSystem,
1438:});
1439:
1440:// Stagger: two interval-2 systems on alternating ticks
1441:world.registerSystem({ name: 'A', execute: a, interval: 2, intervalOffset: 0 }); // ticks 1, 3, 5
1442:world.registerSystem({ name: 'B', execute: b, interval: 2, intervalOffset: 1 }); // ticks 2, 4, 6
1443:```
1444:
1445:#### `step()`
1446:
1447:```typescript
1448:step(): void
1449:```
1450:
1451:Advances the simulation by exactly one tick. **Deterministic** — ignores pause state and speed multiplier. This is the primary method for testing and AI-driven simulations.
1452:
1453:Each tick executes in this order:
1454:
1455:1. Clear event buffer
1456:2. Clear dirty flags (entities, components, resources)
1457:3. Process commands (drain queue, run handlers)
1458:4. Run systems (`input`, `preUpdate`, `update`, `postUpdate`, `output`); periodic systems gated by their `interval` / `intervalOffset` are skipped on non-firing ticks
1459:5. Process resource rates and transfers
1460:6. Build diff (collect dirty state into `TickDiff`)
1461:7. Update metrics
1462:8. Notify diff listeners
1463:9. Increment tick counter
1464:
1465:The spatial grid is updated lock-step with every position write (`setPosition`, `setComponent` on the configured position key) — there is no separate sync phase.
1466:
1467:```typescript
1468:world.step(); // always executes, even when paused
1469:```
1470:
1471:**Throws:** `WorldTickFailureError` if the tick fails at runtime.
1472:
1473:When `instrumentationProfile` is `'minimal'`, `step()` records only coarse implicit metrics. When it is `'release'`, `step()` skips implicit per-tick metrics collection entirely. Use `stepWithResult()` when the caller explicitly wants structured runtime diagnostics.
1474:
1475:#### `stepWithResult()`
1476:
1477:```typescript
1478:stepWithResult(): WorldStepResult
1479:```
1480:
1481:Advances the simulation by exactly one tick and returns a structured success/failure result instead of throwing on runtime failure. This is the preferred stepping API for AI loops and remote harnesses.
1482:
1483:If the world is poisoned (a previous tick failed and `recover()` has not been called), `stepWithResult()` immediately returns `{ ok: false, failure: { code: 'world_poisoned', ... } }` without attempting another tick.
1484:
1485:#### `isPoisoned()`
1486:
1487:```typescript
1488:isPoisoned(): boolean
1489:```
1490:
1491:Returns `true` while the world is in a post-failure poisoned state. Cleared by `recover()`. See Tick failure semantics.
1492:
1493:#### `recover()`
1494:
1495:```typescript
1496:recover(): void
1497:```
1498:
1499:Clears the poison flag along with cached `lastTickFailure`, `currentDiff`, and `currentMetrics`. After `recover()` the world is safe to step again. The next successful tick uses a tick number one greater than the failed tick (failed ticks consume their tick number).
1500:
1501:```typescript
1502:try {
1503:  world.step();
1504:} catch (err) {
1505:  if (err instanceof WorldTickFailureError) {
1506:    console.error('tick failed:', err.failure);
1507:    world.recover();
1508:  }
1509:}
1510:world.step(); // safe again
1511:```
1512:
1513:#### `warnIfPoisoned(api)`
1514:
1515:```typescript
1516:warnIfPoisoned(api: string): void
1517:```
1518:
1519:Emits a `console.warn` once per poison cycle if the world is poisoned (a prior tick failed and `recover()` has not been called). The warning identifies which API surface the caller routed through (`api='submit'`, `api='serialize'`, `api='transaction'`, etc.) so log readers can correlate the warning with the offending call site. Subsequent calls within the same poison cycle are silent; once `recover()` clears the poison, the next `warnIfPoisoned` call after a future failure will warn again.
1520:
1521:This is the integration point used by `submitWithResult`, `serialize`, and `CommandTransaction.commit` to surface "you forgot to recover" without blocking the call. Any new write surface should call this with its own `api` tag for consistency with the rest of the engine.
1522:
1523:```typescript
1524:world.warnIfPoisoned('myCustomCommand');
1525:// → "myCustomCommand called on a poisoned world (last failure: 'system_threw' at tick 5). Call world.recover() to clear the poison flag."
1526:```
1527:
1528:#### `start()`
1529:
1530:```typescript
1531:start(): void
1532:```
1533:
1534:Begins the real-time loop. Ticks accumulate based on elapsed time and the configured TPS. Uses a fixed-timestep algorithm with spiral-of-death protection (controlled by `maxTicksPerFrame`).
1535:
1536:```typescript
1537:world.start(); // begins ticking at TPS rate
1538:```
1539:
1540:#### `stop()`
1541:
1542:```typescript
1543:stop(): void
1544:```
1545:
1546:Stops the real-time loop. The tick counter is preserved.
1547:
1548:```typescript
1549:world.stop();
1550:```
1551:
1552:#### `tick`
1553:
1554:```typescript
1555:get tick(): number
1556:```
1557:
1558:Read-only property returning the current tick count. Starts at `0`, increments by 1 after each tick.
1559:
1560:```typescript
1561:console.log(world.tick); // 0
1562:world.step();
1563:console.log(world.tick); // 1
1564:```
1565:
1566:#### `grid`
1567:
1568:```typescript
1569:readonly grid: SpatialGrid
1570:```
1571:
1572:Read-only reference to the spatial grid. Use `grid.getAt()` and `grid.getNeighbors()` to query spatial data. Do not call `grid.insert()`, `grid.remove()`, or `grid.move()` directly — the World handles spatial sync automatically.
1573:
1574:### Speed Control
1575:
1576:#### `setSpeed(multiplier)`
1577:
1578:```typescript
1579:setSpeed(multiplier: number): void
1580:```
1581:
1582:Sets the simulation speed multiplier for the real-time loop. `2` means ticks accumulate twice as fast. `0.5` means half speed. Has no effect on `step()`.
1583:
1584:**Throws:** `Error` if `multiplier` is not a finite positive number (rejects `0`, negative, `NaN`, `Infinity`).
1585:
1586:```typescript
1587:world.setSpeed(2);    // double speed
1588:world.setSpeed(0.5);  // half speed
1589:```
1590:
1591:#### `getSpeed()`
1592:
1593:```typescript
1594:getSpeed(): number
1595:```
1596:
1597:Returns the current speed multiplier. Default is `1`.
1598:
1599:#### `pause()`
1600:
1601:```typescript
1602:pause(): void
1603:```
1604:
1605:Pauses the real-time loop. The speed multiplier is preserved. `step()` still works while paused.
1606:
1607:#### `resume()`
1608:
1609:```typescript
1610:resume(): void
1611:```
1612:
1613:Resumes the real-time loop at the current speed multiplier. Resets the time accumulator to prevent a burst of ticks.
1614:
1615:#### `isPaused`
1616:
1617:```typescript
1618:get isPaused(): boolean
1619:```
1620:
1621:Read-only property. `true` when the simulation is paused.
1622:
1623:### Commands
1624:
1625:Commands are validated-and-queued input from external code (AI agents, UI). They are processed at the start of each tick, before spatial sync and systems.
1626:
1627:#### `submit<K>(type, data)`
1628:
1629:```typescript
1630:submit<K extends keyof TCommandMap>(type: K, data: TCommandMap[K]): boolean
1631:```
1632:
1633:Submits a command. All registered validators for this command type are run immediately (synchronously). If any validator rejects, the command is not queued.
1634:
1635:**Returns:** `true` if the command passed all validators and was queued, `false` if rejected. This is the compatibility wrapper over `submitWithResult()`; the two paths produce identical observable outcomes (same validator pipeline, same `submissionSequence` assignment, same listener emissions). Use `submitWithResult()` when the caller wants the full structured `CommandSubmissionResult`.
1636:
1637:```typescript
1638:const accepted = world.submit('moveUnit', { entityId: 0, targetX: 5, targetY: 3 });
1639:// accepted: true if validation passed
1640:```
1641:
1642:#### `submitWithResult<K>(type, data)`
1643:
1644:```typescript
1645:submitWithResult<K extends keyof TCommandMap>(
1646:  type: K,
1647:  data: TCommandMap[K],
1648:): CommandSubmissionResult<K>
1649:```
1650:
1651:Submits a command and returns the full structured outcome.
1652:
1653:```typescript
1654:const result = world.submitWithResult('moveUnit', {
1655:  entityId: 0,
1656:  targetX: 5,
1657:  targetY: 3,
1658:});
1659:```
1660:
1661:#### `registerValidator<K>(type, fn)`
1662:
1663:```typescript
1664:registerValidator<K extends keyof TCommandMap>(
1665:  type: K,
1666:  fn: (
1667:    data: TCommandMap[K],
1668:    world: World<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>,
1669:  ) => CommandValidationResult,
1670:): void
1671:```
1672:
1673:Adds a validator for a command type. Multiple validators can be registered per type — they short-circuit on the first `false` return.
1674:
1675:```typescript
1676:world.registerValidator('moveUnit', (data, w) => {
1677:  return w.isAlive(data.entityId);
1678:});
1679:```
1680:
1681:Validators may also return a structured rejection object:
1682:
1683:```typescript
1684:world.registerValidator('moveUnit', (data, w) => {
1685:  if (!w.isAlive(data.entityId)) {
1686:    return {
1687:      code: 'dead_entity',
1688:      message: 'Entity is not alive',
1689:      details: { entityId: data.entityId },
1690:    };
1691:  }
1692:  return true;
1693:});
1694:```
1695:
1696:#### `registerHandler<K>(type, fn)`
1697:
1698:```typescript
1699:registerHandler<K extends keyof TCommandMap>(
1700:  type: K,
1701:  fn: (
1702:    data: TCommandMap[K],
1703:    world: World<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>,
1704:  ) => void,
1705:): void
1706:```
1707:
1708:Sets the handler for a command type. Exactly one handler per type. The handler runs at tick start when commands are processed.
1709:
1710:**Throws:** `Error` if a handler is already registered for this command type.
1711:
1712:When a command is processed but no handler is registered, the tick fails with a structured `TickFailure`. `world.step()` surfaces that failure as `WorldTickFailureError`. `ClientAdapter` checks this ahead of time and rejects unhandled client commands before they enter the queue.
1713:
1714:```typescript
1715:world.registerHandler('moveUnit', (data, w) => {
1716:  w.setPosition(data.entityId, { x: data.targetX, y: data.targetY });
1717:});
1718:```
1719:
1720:#### `hasCommandHandler(type)`
1721:
1722:```typescript
1723:hasCommandHandler(type: keyof TCommandMap): boolean
1724:```
1725:
1726:Returns whether a handler is registered for the command type. This is primarily useful for transport adapters that need to reject unhandled commands before enqueueing them.
1727:
1728:#### `onCommandResult(listener)`
1729:
1730:```typescript
1731:onCommandResult(
1732:  listener: (result: CommandSubmissionResult<keyof TCommandMap>) => void,
1733:): void
1734:```
1735:
1736:Subscribes to accepted and rejected command submission results.
1737:
1738:#### `offCommandResult(listener)`
1739:
1740:```typescript
1741:offCommandResult(
1742:  listener: (result: CommandSubmissionResult<keyof TCommandMap>) => void,
1743:): void
1744:```
1745:
1746:Removes a command-result listener.
1747:
1748:#### `onCommandExecution(listener)`
1749:
1750:```typescript
1751:onCommandExecution(
1752:  listener: (result: CommandExecutionResult<keyof TCommandMap>) => void,
1753:): void
1754:```
1755:
1756:Subscribes to tick-time command execution results.
1757:
1758:#### `offCommandExecution(listener)`
1759:
1760:```typescript
1761:offCommandExecution(
1762:  listener: (result: CommandExecutionResult<keyof TCommandMap>) => void,
1763:): void
1764:```
1765:
1766:Removes a command-execution listener.
1767:
1768:#### `onTickFailure(listener)`
1769:
1770:```typescript
1771:onTickFailure(listener: (failure: TickFailure) => void): void
1772:```
1773:
1774:Subscribes to structured tick failures.
1775:
1776:#### `offTickFailure(listener)`
1777:
1778:```typescript
1779:offTickFailure(listener: (failure: TickFailure) => void): void
1780:```
1781:
1782:Removes a tick-failure listener.
1783:
1784:### Events
1785:
1786:Events are a typed pub/sub mechanism for system-to-system communication and external observation. Events are buffered per tick and cleared at the start of the next tick.
1787:
1788:#### `emit<K>(type, data)`
1789:
1790:```typescript
1791:emit<K extends keyof TEventMap>(type: K, data: TEventMap[K]): void
1792:```
1793:
1794:Emits an event. The event is added to the tick buffer and all registered listeners are called immediately (synchronously).
1795:
1796:```typescript
1797:world.emit('unitDied', { entityId: 5, cause: 'starvation' });
1798:```
1799:
1800:#### `on<K>(type, listener)`
1801:
1802:```typescript
1803:on<K extends keyof TEventMap>(type: K, listener: (event: TEventMap[K]) => void): void
1804:```
1805:
1806:Subscribes to an event type. The listener fires each time an event of this type is emitted.
1807:
1808:```typescript
1809:world.on('unitDied', (event) => {
1810:  console.log(`Unit ${event.entityId} died from ${event.cause}`);
1811:});
1812:```
1813:
1814:#### `off<K>(type, listener)`
1815:
1816:```typescript
1817:off<K extends keyof TEventMap>(type: K, listener: (event: TEventMap[K]) => void): void
1818:```
1819:
1820:Unsubscribes from an event type. Pass the exact same function reference used in `on()`.
1821:
1822:#### `getEvents()`
1823:
1824:```typescript
1825:getEvents(): ReadonlyArray<{ type: keyof TEventMap; data: TEventMap[keyof TEventMap] }>
1826:```
1827:
1828:Returns all events emitted during the current tick. The returned array is read-only. Cleared at the start of each tick.
1829:
1830:```typescript
1831:world.step();
1832:for (const event of world.getEvents()) {
1833:  console.log(event.type, event.data);
1834:}
1835:```
1836:
1837:### Randomness
1838:
1839:#### `random()`
1840:
1841:```typescript
1842:random(): number
1843:```
1844:
1845:Returns a deterministic pseudo-random number in `[0, 1)`. Worlds created with the same `seed` produce the same sequence, and snapshot version 3 stores the RNG state so `World.deserialize()` resumes from the exact next value.
1846:
1847:```typescript
1848:const world = new World({ gridWidth: 64, gridHeight: 64, tps: 10, seed: 'map-42' });
1849:const roll = world.random();
1850:```
1851:
1852:### Resources
1853:
1854:Resources are numeric pools (current/max) attached to entities with automatic production, consumption, and inter-entity transfers. Resource rates and transfers are processed after systems each tick.
1855:
1856:#### `registerResource(key, options?)`
1857:
1858:```typescript
1859:registerResource(key: string, options?: { defaultMax?: number | null }): void
1860:```
1861:
1862:Registers a resource type. Must be called before using any resource methods with this key.
1863:
1864:**Throws:** `Error` if the resource key is already registered.
1865:
1866:| Option | Type | Default | Description |
1867:|---|---|---|---|
1868:| `defaultMax` | `number \| null` | `null` | Default maximum capacity for new pools; `null` means unbounded |
1869:
1870:```typescript
1871:world.registerResource('food');
1872:world.registerResource('gold', { defaultMax: 1000 });
1873:```
1874:
1875:#### `addResource(entity, key, amount)`
1876:
1877:```typescript
1878:addResource(entity: EntityId, key: string, amount: number): number
1879:```
1880:
1881:Adds to an entity's resource pool. Creates the pool if it doesn't exist (with the resource type's `defaultMax`). Clamped to the pool's maximum.
1882:
1883:**Returns:** The amount actually added (may be less than requested if the pool is near max).
1884:
1885:**Throws:** `Error` if the resource key is not registered, the entity is not alive, or `amount` is negative/non-finite.
1886:
1887:```typescript
1888:const added = world.addResource(city, 'food', 50); // returns 50 (or less if near cap)
1889:```
1890:
1891:#### `removeResource(entity, key, amount)`
1892:
1893:```typescript
1894:removeResource(entity: EntityId, key: string, amount: number): number
1895:```
1896:
1897:Removes from an entity's resource pool. Clamped to the current value (cannot go below 0).
1898:
1899:**Returns:** The amount actually removed.
1900:
1901:```typescript
1902:const removed = world.removeResource(city, 'food', 30);
1903:```
1904:
1905:#### `getResource(entity, key)`
1906:
1907:```typescript
1908:getResource(entity: EntityId, key: string): { current: number; max: number | null } | undefined
1909:```
1910:
1911:Returns a copy of the resource pool for the given entity, or `undefined` if the entity has no pool for this resource.
1912:
1913:```typescript
1914:const pool = world.getResource(city, 'food');
1915:if (pool) {
1916:  console.log(`${pool.current}/${pool.max}`);
1917:}
1918:```
1919:
1920:#### `setResourceMax(entity, key, max)`
1921:
1922:```typescript
1923:setResourceMax(entity: EntityId, key: string, max: number | null): void
1924:```
1925:
1926:Sets the maximum capacity for a resource pool. If `current` exceeds the new max, it is clamped down. Use `null` for unbounded capacity. No-op if the entity has no pool for this resource.
1927:
1928:```typescript
1929:world.setResourceMax(city, 'food', 200);
1930:```
1931:
1932:#### `setProduction(entity, key, rate)`
1933:
1934:```typescript
1935:setProduction(entity: EntityId, key: string, rate: number): void
1936:```
1937:
1938:Sets the per-tick production rate. A pool is auto-created if one doesn't exist. Set to `0` to remove the production rate.
1939:
1940:```typescript
1941:world.setProduction(farm, 'food', 5); // +5 food/tick
1942:world.setProduction(farm, 'food', 0); // stop producing
1943:```
1944:
1945:#### `setConsumption(entity, key, rate)`
1946:
1947:```typescript
1948:setConsumption(entity: EntityId, key: string, rate: number): void
1949:```
1950:
1951:Sets the per-tick consumption rate. Does not auto-create a pool. Set to `0` to remove the consumption rate.
1952:
1953:```typescript
1954:world.setConsumption(city, 'food', 2); // -2 food/tick
1955:```
1956:
1957:#### `getProduction(entity, key)`
1958:
1959:```typescript
1960:getProduction(entity: EntityId, key: string): number
1961:```
1962:
1963:Returns the production rate for an entity/resource, or `0` if none set.
1964:
1965:#### `getConsumption(entity, key)`
1966:
1967:```typescript
1968:getConsumption(entity: EntityId, key: string): number
1969:```
1970:
1971:Returns the consumption rate for an entity/resource, or `0` if none set.
1972:
1973:#### `addTransfer(from, to, resource, rate)`
1974:
1975:```typescript
1976:addTransfer(from: EntityId, to: EntityId, resource: string, rate: number): number
1977:```
1978:
1979:Creates a recurring resource transfer. Each tick, up to `rate` units are moved from the source entity's pool to the destination entity's pool (clamped by source availability and destination capacity).
1980:
1981:Transfers involving dead entities are automatically removed during tick processing.
1982:
1983:**Returns:** A unique transfer ID (for later removal with `removeTransfer`).
1984:
1985:```typescript
1986:const transferId = world.addTransfer(farm, city, 'food', 3); // 3 food/tick
1987:```
1988:
1989:#### `removeTransfer(id)`
1990:
1991:```typescript
1992:removeTransfer(id: number): void
1993:```
1994:
1995:Removes a transfer by its ID.
1996:
1997:```typescript
1998:world.removeTransfer(transferId);
1999:```
2000:
2001:#### `getTransfers(entity)`
2002:
2003:```typescript
2004:getTransfers(entity: EntityId): Array<{
2005:  id: number;
2006:  from: EntityId;
2007:  to: EntityId;
2008:  resource: string;
2009:  rate: number;
2010:}>
2011:```
2012:
2013:Returns all transfers that involve the given entity (as source or destination).
2014:
2015:#### `getResourceEntities(key)`
2016:
2017:```typescript
2018:*getResourceEntities(key: string): IterableIterator<EntityId>
2019:```
2020:
2021:Iterates all entities that have a pool for this resource.
2022:
2023:```typescript
2024:for (const id of world.getResourceEntities('food')) {
2025:  const pool = world.getResource(id, 'food')!;
2026:  console.log(`Entity ${id}: ${pool.current} food`);
2027:}
2028:```
2029:
2030:### World State
2031:
2032:Non-entity structured state stored at the world level. Values must be JSON-compatible. World state is included in serialization (snapshot v5) and tick diffs.
2033:
2034:#### `setState(key, value)`
2035:
2036:```typescript
2037:setState(key: string, value: unknown): void
2038:```
2039:
2040:Stores a world-level state value under the given key. Overwrites any existing value for that key. The value must be JSON-compatible.
2041:
2042:```typescript
2043:world.setState('turnNumber', 1);
2044:world.setState('diplomacy', { alliances: [], wars: [] });
2045:```
2046:
2047:#### `getState(key)`
2048:
2049:```typescript
2050:getState(key: string): unknown
2051:```
2052:
2053:Retrieves a world-level state value by key, or `undefined` if the key does not exist.
2054:
2055:```typescript
2056:const turn = world.getState('turnNumber'); // 1
2057:```
2058:
2059:#### `deleteState(key)`
2060:
2061:```typescript
2062:deleteState(key: string): void
2063:```
2064:
2065:Removes a world-level state entry. No-op if the key does not exist.
2066:
2067:```typescript
2068:world.deleteState('diplomacy');
2069:```
2070:
2071:#### `hasState(key)`
2072:
2073:```typescript
2074:hasState(key: string): boolean
2075:```
2076:
2077:Returns `true` if the world has a state entry for the given key.
2078:
2079:```typescript
2080:if (world.hasState('turnNumber')) {
2081:  // ...
2082:}
2083:```
2084:
2085:### Tags & Metadata
2086:
2087:String tags and key-value metadata attached to individual entities. Both are cleaned up automatically on `destroyEntity()` and included in serialization (snapshot v5) and tick diffs.
2088:
2089:#### `addTag(entity, tag)`
2090:
2091:```typescript
2092:addTag(entity: EntityId, tag: string): void
2093:```
2094:
2095:Adds a string label to an entity. No-op if the entity already has the tag.
2096:
2097:```typescript
2098:world.addTag(unit, 'selected');
2099:world.addTag(unit, 'military');
2100:```
2101:
2102:#### `removeTag(entity, tag)`
2103:
2104:```typescript
2105:removeTag(entity: EntityId, tag: string): void
2106:```
2107:
2108:Removes a tag from an entity. No-op if the entity does not have the tag.
2109:
2110:```typescript
2111:world.removeTag(unit, 'selected');
2112:```
2113:
2114:#### `hasTag(entity, tag)`
2115:
2116:```typescript
2117:hasTag(entity: EntityId, tag: string): boolean
2118:```
2119:
2120:Returns `true` if the entity has the given tag.
2121:
2122:```typescript
2123:if (world.hasTag(unit, 'military')) {
2124:  // ...
2125:}
2126:```
2127:
2128:#### `getByTag(tag)`
2129:
2130:```typescript
2131:getByTag(tag: string): ReadonlySet<EntityId>
2132:```
2133:
2134:Returns all entities that have the given tag. The returned set is read-only.
2135:
2136:```typescript
2137:for (const id of world.getByTag('military')) {
2138:  // process each military entity
2139:}
2140:```
2141:
2142:#### `getTags(entity)`
2143:
2144:```typescript
2145:getTags(entity: EntityId): ReadonlySet<string>
2146:```
2147:
2148:Returns all tags for an entity. The returned set is read-only.
2149:
2150:```typescript
2151:const tags = world.getTags(unit); // ReadonlySet<string>
2152:```
2153:
2154:#### `setMeta(entity, key, value)`
2155:
2156:```typescript
2157:setMeta(entity: EntityId, key: string, value: string | number): void
2158:```
2159:
2160:Sets a metadata key-value pair on an entity. Metadata values are restricted to `string` or `number`.
2161:
2162:```typescript
2163:world.setMeta(unit, 'owner', 'player1');
2164:world.setMeta(unit, 'level', 3);
2165:```
2166:
2167:#### `getMeta(entity, key)`
2168:
2169:```typescript
2170:getMeta(entity: EntityId, key: string): string | number | undefined
2171:```
2172:
2173:Returns the metadata value for the given entity and key, or `undefined` if not set.
2174:
2175:```typescript
2176:const owner = world.getMeta(unit, 'owner'); // 'player1'
2177:```
2178:
2179:#### `deleteMeta(entity, key)`
2180:
2181:```typescript
2182:deleteMeta(entity: EntityId, key: string): void
2183:```
2184:
2185:Removes a metadata entry from an entity. No-op if the key does not exist.
2186:
2187:```typescript
2188:world.deleteMeta(unit, 'owner');
2189:```
2190:
2191:#### `getByMeta(key, value)`
2192:
2193:```typescript
2194:getByMeta(key: string, value: string | number): EntityId | undefined
2195:```
2196:
2197:Reverse lookup: finds the entity that has the given metadata key-value pair. Returns `undefined` if no entity matches.
2198:
2199:```typescript
2200:const player1Unit = world.getByMeta('owner', 'player1');
2201:```
2202:
2203:### Spatial Queries
2204:
2205:Higher-level spatial query helpers built on top of the spatial grid and component stores.
2206:
2207:#### `queryInRadius(cx, cy, radius, ...components)`
2208:
2209:```typescript
2210:queryInRadius(
2211:  cx: number,
2212:  cy: number,
2213:  radius: number,
2214:  ...components: string[]
2215:): EntityId[]
2216:```
2217:
2218:Returns all entities within the given radius of `(cx, cy)` that match all specified components. Uses Euclidean distance.
2219:
2220:```typescript
2221:const nearby = world.queryInRadius(10, 10, 5, 'position', 'health');
2222:```
2223:
2224:#### `findNearest(cx, cy, ...components)`
2225:
2226:```typescript
2227:findNearest(
2228:  cx: number,
2229:  cy: number,
2230:  ...components: string[]
2231:): EntityId | undefined
2232:```
2233:
2234:Returns the closest entity to `(cx, cy)` that matches all specified components, or `undefined` if no entity matches. Uses Euclidean distance.
2235:
2236:```typescript
2237:const closest = world.findNearest(10, 10, 'position', 'enemy');
2238:```
2239:
2240:### State Serialization
2241:
2242:#### `serialize(options?)`
2243:
2244:```typescript
2245:serialize(options?: { inspectPoisoned?: boolean }): WorldSnapshot
2246:```
2247:
2248:Captures the entire world state as a JSON-serializable snapshot. Includes entity state, all component data, resource state, grid config, and tick count. Does **not** include systems, validators, handlers, or event listeners (they are functions). Component data and state values are `structuredClone`d on the way out so the returned snapshot stays isolated from the live world.
2249:
2250:When called on a poisoned world, `serialize()` emits a one-time `console.warn` per poison cycle. Pass `{ inspectPoisoned: true }` to suppress the warning — intended for engine-internal debug/history tooling that exists specifically to inspect poisoned state. The warning resets on `world.recover()`.
2251:
2252:```typescript
2253:const snapshot = world.serialize();
2254:const json = JSON.stringify(snapshot);
2255:```
2256:
2257:#### `World.deserialize(snapshot, systems?)`
2258:
2259:```typescript
2260:static deserialize<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>(
2261:  snapshot: WorldSnapshot,
2262:  systems?: Array<
2263:    | System<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>
2264:    | SystemRegistration<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>
2265:    | LooseSystem
2266:    | LooseSystemRegistration
2267:  >,
2268:): World<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>
2269:```
2270:
2271:Restores a world from a snapshot. Optionally accepts systems to re-register. After deserializing, you must also re-register:
2272:- Command validators and handlers
2273:- Event listeners
2274:- Destroy callbacks
2275:
2276:Component data and state values are `structuredClone`d on read so the input snapshot stays isolated from the live world.
2277:
2278:**Throws:**
2279:- `Error` if `snapshot.version` is not `1`, `2`, `3`, `4`, or `5`
2280:- `Error` if entity state arrays have mismatched lengths
2281:- `Error` if `snapshot.tags` or `snapshot.metadata` references a dead entity id
2282:
2283:Version 1 snapshots load with an empty resource store. Version 2 snapshots restore resource registrations, pools, rates, transfers, and the next transfer ID. Version 3 snapshots also restore deterministic RNG state. Version 4 snapshots also restore world-level state, entity tags, and entity metadata. Version 5 snapshots additionally round-trip per-component `ComponentStoreOptions` (`diffMode`) plus `WorldConfig.maxTicksPerFrame` and `WorldConfig.instrumentationProfile` when non-default.
2284:
2285:```typescript
2286:const restored = World.deserialize(snapshot, [movementSystem, combatSystem]);
2287:restored.registerValidator('moveUnit', validator);
2288:restored.registerHandler('moveUnit', handler);
2289:```
2290:
2291:### State Diffs
2292:
2293:#### `getDiff()`
2294:
2295:```typescript
2296:getDiff(): TickDiff | null
2297:```
2298:
2299:Returns the diff from the most recent tick, or `null` if no tick has been executed yet. The diff is rebuilt each tick.
2300:
2301:```typescript
2302:world.step();
2303:const diff = world.getDiff();
2304:if (diff) {
2305:  console.log(`Created: ${diff.entities.created}`);
2306:  console.log(`Destroyed: ${diff.entities.destroyed}`);
2307:}
2308:```
2309:
2310:#### `getMetrics()`
2311:
2312:```typescript
2313:getMetrics(): WorldMetrics | null
2314:```
2315:
2316:Returns timing and count instrumentation from the most recent tick, or `null` before the first tick. Metrics include simulation budget data, last-tick command counts, entity/component counts, query cache hit/miss counts, the per-tick `spatial.explicitSyncs` count (incremented by every `setPosition`-style write), system timings, and tick section timings.
2317:
2318:In `instrumentationProfile: 'minimal'`, implicit `step()` still updates counts and total duration, but leaves detailed phase timings and per-system timing entries empty. In `instrumentationProfile: 'release'`, implicit `step()` leaves this as `null` so the shipping runtime does not pay for per-tick metrics. Explicit `stepWithResult()` calls still populate the full metrics payload for callers that deliberately opt into richer diagnostics.
2319:
2320:```typescript
2321:world.step();
2322:const metrics = world.getMetrics();
2323:console.log(metrics?.query.cacheHits, metrics?.durationMs.total);
2324:```
2325:
2326:#### `getInstrumentationProfile()`
2327:
2328:```typescript
2329:getInstrumentationProfile(): InstrumentationProfile
2330:```
2331:
2332:Returns the active instrumentation profile for this `World`.
2333:
2334:#### `getLastTickFailure()`
2335:
2336:```typescript
2337:getLastTickFailure(): TickFailure | null
2338:```
2339:
2340:Returns the most recent structured tick failure, or `null` if no tick has failed yet.
2341:
2342:#### `onDiff(fn)`
2343:
2344:```typescript
2345:onDiff(fn: (diff: TickDiff) => void): void
2346:```
2347:
2348:Subscribes to per-tick diffs. The callback fires at the end of each tick, after systems and resource processing.
2349:
2350:```typescript
2351:world.onDiff((diff) => {
2352:  // send to client, log, etc.
2353:});
2354:```
2355:
2356:#### `offDiff(fn)`
2357:
2358:```typescript
2359:offDiff(fn: (diff: TickDiff) => void): void
2360:```
2361:
2362:Unsubscribes from diffs. Pass the exact same function reference used in `onDiff()`.
2363:
2364:### Entity Lifecycle Hooks
2365:
2366:#### `onDestroy(callback)`
2367:
2368:```typescript
2369:onDestroy(
2370:  callback: (id: EntityId, world: World<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>) => void,
2371:): void
2372:```
2373:
2374:Registers a callback that fires when any entity is destroyed, **before** its components are removed. This allows cleanup logic (e.g., removing references from other entities).
2375:
2376:Multiple callbacks can be registered. They fire in registration order.
2377:
2378:```typescript
2379:world.onDestroy((id, w) => {
2380:  // Entity still has its components here
2381:  const owner = w.getComponent<{ ownerId: EntityId }>(id, 'owned');
2382:  if (owner) {
2383:    // clean up reference on the owner entity
2384:  }
2385:});
2386:```
2387:
2388:#### `offDestroy(callback)`
2389:
2390:```typescript
2391:offDestroy(
2392:  callback: (id: EntityId, world: World<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>) => void,
2393:): void
2394:```
2395:
2396:Unregisters a destroy callback. Pass the exact same function reference used in `onDestroy()`.
2397:
