3396:
3397:## Command Transaction
3398:
3399:Atomic propose-validate-commit-or-abort builder over `World`. Buffers proposed mutations, events, and precondition predicates; on `commit()` either applies everything (preconditions passed) or applies nothing (any precondition failed). v1 surface: components, position, events, resources. Inspired by MicropolisCore's `ToolEffects` (`MicropolisEngine/src/tool.h:171`).
3400:
3401:```typescript
3402:import { CommandTransaction, type TransactionResult } from 'civ-engine';
3403:```
3404:
3405:### `world.transaction()`
3406:
3407:```typescript
3408:transaction(): CommandTransaction<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>
3409:```
3410:
3411:Creates a fresh transaction bound to this world. The returned transaction inherits all four of the world's generics, so typed component / state / event access works inside the transaction the same way it works against `world.setComponent` / `world.emit` directly. `world.transaction().setComponent(e, 'hp', { wrong: 5 })` against `World<..., ..., { hp: { current: number } }, ...>` is a TypeScript error matching `world.setComponent`.
3412:
3413:### Builder methods (chainable, return `this`)
3414:
3415:| Method | Buffers |
3416:|---|---|
3417:| `setComponent(entity, key, data)` | A `setComponent` mutation |
3418:| `addComponent(entity, key, data)` | Alias for `setComponent` (matches `World.addComponent`) |
3419:| `patchComponent(entity, key, patch)` | A `patchComponent` mutation; `patch` runs at commit time against current state |
3420:| `removeComponent(entity, key)` | A `removeComponent` mutation |
3421:| `setPosition(entity, position, key?)` | A `setPosition` mutation; `key` defaults to the world's `positionKey` |
3422:| `addResource(entity, resource, amount)` | An `addResource` mutation |
3423:| `removeResource(entity, resource, amount)` | A `removeResource` mutation |
3424:| `emit(type, data)` | A buffered event; emitted via `EventBus` only on successful commit |
3425:| `require(predicate)` | A precondition; `predicate(world)` runs before any mutation applies |
3426:
3427:All builder methods throw if the transaction has already been committed or aborted.
3428:
3429:### Preconditions
3430:
3431:```typescript
3432:type TransactionPrecondition<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState> =
3433:  (world: ReadOnlyTransactionWorld<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>)
3434:    => true | false | string;
3435:```
3436:
3437:A predicate receives a **read-only façade** of the world and must return one of:
3438:
3439:- `true` — pass
3440:- `false` — fail (rejection reason: `"precondition returned false"`)
3441:- a `string` — fail (rejection reason: the string)
3442:
3443:`ReadOnlyTransactionWorld` is `Omit<World, K>` where `K` is the exhaustive `FORBIDDEN_PRECONDITION_METHODS` array. Every public mutation, lifecycle, listener-subscription, RNG, and sub-engine method on `World` is excluded — including `random` (because it advances `DeterministicRandom.state`), `setProduction` / `setConsumption` / `setResourceMax`, `start` / `stop` / `pause` / `resume` / `setSpeed`, every `on*` / `off*` listener subscription, and `warnIfPoisoned` (consumes the warn-once latch). Predicates may freely call read methods (`getComponent`, `hasResource`, `getState`, `getInRadius`, `findNearest`, `getByTag`, etc.). Three structurally-different mechanisms enforce side-effect freedom:
3444:
3445:1. **Method-name denylist.** Calling a forbidden method fails to typecheck; if the type is cast away, the runtime proxy throws `CommandTransaction precondition cannot call '<method>': preconditions must be side-effect free`. A property-based meta-test cross-checks `FORBIDDEN_PRECONDITION_METHODS` against `Object.getOwnPropertyNames(World.prototype)` so future World additions can't slip past silently.
3446:2. **Clone-on-read for live-reference returns.** `getComponent`, `getComponents`, `getState`, `getResource`, `getTags`, `getByTag`, and `getEvents` return values that point into engine-owned storage. The proxy `structuredClone`s their results before the predicate sees them, so a predicate that mutates a returned object — e.g. `w.getComponent(e, 'hp')!.current = 0` — operates on a defensive copy and the live state stays untouched.
3447:3. **Frozen sub-objects.** `world.grid` is the only public field that is a sub-object rather than a prototype method. It is `Object.freeze`d in the constructor, so monkey-patching `w.grid.getAt = () => null` from inside a predicate throws `TypeError` in strict mode.
3448:
3449:Preconditions run in registration order at the start of `commit()` and short-circuit on the first failure. Each predicate sees the **current live state** of the world, not the transaction's proposed mutations — preconditions are checked against the pre-commit baseline, not the post-commit projection.
3450:
3451:### `commit(): TransactionResult`
3452:
3453:```typescript
3454:type TransactionResult =
3455:  | { ok: true;  mutationsApplied: number; eventsEmitted: number }
3456:  | { ok: false; code: 'precondition_failed'; reason: string }
3457:  | { ok: false; code: 'aborted' };
3458:```
3459:
3460:Runs preconditions; on any failure, returns `precondition_failed` with no mutation or event applied. Otherwise applies every buffered mutation in registration order via the corresponding public `World` API (so mutations get the same liveness, bounds, and JSON-compat validation as direct calls), then emits every buffered event via `world.emit`. Returns the success result with counts.
3461:
3462:If the transaction was previously `abort()`ed, `commit()` returns `{ ok: false, code: 'aborted' }` without throwing or mutating.
3463:
3464:`commit()` on a transaction that has already reached a terminal state throws `Error('CommandTransaction already <terminalReason>')` where `<terminalReason>` is `'committed'` after a clean commit and `'aborted'` after an `abort()` followed by `commit()` (which returns `{ ok: false, code: 'aborted' }` once and then transitions to a terminal state). Builder methods (`setComponent`, `emit`, `require`, etc.) throw the same error for the same reason.
3465:
3466:### `abort(): void`
3467:
3468:Marks a pending transaction as aborted. A subsequent `commit()` returns `{ ok: false, code: 'aborted' }` with no mutation or event applied. `abort()` on an already-committed or already-aborted transaction is a no-op.
3469:
3470:### v1 limitations
3471:
3472:- **Unbuffered ops:** `createEntity`, `destroyEntity`, `addTag`, `removeTag`, `setMeta`, `deleteMeta`, `setState`, `deleteState`, and resource registration / `setResourceMax` are not buffered. v1 covers components (set / add / patch / remove), position, events, and resource add / remove.
3473:- **Aliasing window.** Buffered values (the `data` argument to `setComponent` / `addComponent` / `patchComponent`, the `position` argument to `setPosition`, and the `data` argument to `emit`) are stored by reference. Mutating a buffered object between the builder call and `commit()` is observable at apply time. Treat buffered values as owned by the transaction once handed over.
3474:- **Mid-commit throw → partial state, transaction consumed.** If a buffered mutation throws mid-commit (e.g., entity destroyed between buffering and commit, JSON-incompat caller-side mutation per the aliasing window above, etc.), the error propagates. Mutations 0..N-1 already applied stay applied. The transaction is still consumed (status flips to `committed` in a `finally` block), so calling `commit()` again throws — the caller cannot retry and silently double-apply earlier mutations (e.g., double-debit a resource). Best practice: validate entity liveness via `require((w) => w.isAlive(entity) || 'entity dead')` before mutating.
3475:- **Event payloads are validated at `emit()` buffer time, not at `commit()`.** Calling `emit(type, data)` with a non-JSON-cloneable payload throws immediately at the builder call, before any mutation runs. Listener exceptions during `commit()` still propagate after mutations have applied — the transaction-level "all-or-nothing" promise covers preconditions and JSON-compat validation, not arbitrary exceptions thrown by listener callbacks.
3476:- **Poisoned-world warning.** If `commit()` runs against a world that has not been recovered from a prior tick failure, it emits the standard `console.warn` once per poison cycle (`api='transaction'`). Call `world.recover()` before transacting against a previously-failed world.
3477:
3478:### Example: cost-checked build action
3479:
3480:```typescript
3481:const result = world
3482:  .transaction()
3483:  .require((w) => {
3484:    const wood = w.getResource(player, 'wood');
3485:    return (wood?.current ?? 0) >= 80 || 'not enough wood';
3486:  })
3487:  .removeResource(player, 'wood', 80)
3488:  .setComponent(site, 'building', { kind: 'house' })
3489:  .emit('building_placed', { player, site, kind: 'house' })
3490:  .commit();
3491:
3492:if (!result.ok) {
3493:  console.log('build aborted:', result.code === 'precondition_failed' ? result.reason : result.code);
3494:}
3495:```
3496:
3497:If the player has 80+ wood, the transaction commits: wood is deducted, the building is placed, and the `building_placed` event fires — all in one tick, all visible in one `TickDiff`. If the player has fewer than 80 wood, none of the changes apply and the event is not emitted.
3498:
3499:---
3500:
3501:## Layer
3502:
3503:Generic typed overlay map at configurable downsampled resolution. Models field data — pollution, influence, danger, weather, faith — as a sparse grid where each cell covers a `blockSize × blockSize` block of world coordinates. Standalone utility, no `World` dependency. Sibling of `OccupancyGrid` and `VisibilityMap`.
3504:
3505:```typescript
3506:import { Layer, type LayerState } from 'civ-engine';
3507:```
3508:
3509:### `LayerOptions<T>`
3510:
3511:```typescript
3512:// src/layer.ts
3513:interface LayerOptions<T> {
3514:  worldWidth: number;
3515:  worldHeight: number;
3516:  blockSize?: number;     // default 1
3517:  defaultValue: T;
3518:}
3519:```
3520:
3521:`worldWidth`, `worldHeight`, and `blockSize` (default `1`) must be **safe positive integers** (rejected via `Number.isSafeInteger`). The cell grid dimensions are `Math.ceil(worldWidth / blockSize)` × `Math.ceil(worldHeight / blockSize)`; the constructor also rejects dimensions whose product exceeds `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER` to keep cell-index arithmetic exact. `defaultValue` must be JSON-compatible (validated via `assertJsonCompatible`).
3522:
3523:### `LayerState<T>`
3524:
3525:```typescript
3526:// src/layer.ts
3527:interface LayerState<T> {
3528:  worldWidth: number;
3529:  worldHeight: number;
3530:  blockSize: number;
3531:  defaultValue: T;
3532:  cells: Array<[number, T]>;  // sparse: [cellIndex, value]
3533:}
3534:```
3535:
3536:Sparse serialization. Only cells whose value differs from `defaultValue` (compared by JSON fingerprint) appear in `cells`; entries are sorted by `cellIndex` for determinism. `cellIndex = cy * width + cx`.
3537:
3538:### `new Layer<T>(options)`
3539:
3540:```typescript
3541:new Layer<T>(options: LayerOptions<T>)
3542:```
3543:
3544:Creates a Layer of cell type `T`. The constructor validates dimensions and JSON-compatibility, and `structuredClone`s `defaultValue` so caller mutation cannot bleed in.
3545:
3546:**Defensive-copy contract.** Values flowing across the Layer's API surface are `structuredClone`d for object `T`; for primitive `T` (`number`, `string`, `boolean`, `null`) the clone is skipped because primitives are immutable on the JS side:
3547:
3548:- **Writes** (`setCell`, `setAt`, `fill`): for object `T`, the input value is cloned before storage. Mutating the original after the call does not affect the Layer. For primitive `T`, the value is stored by value (no clone).
3549:- **Reads** (`getCell`, `getAt`, `forEach`, `defaultValue` getter): for object `T`, the returned value is a fresh clone of internal storage. For primitive `T`, the value is returned directly.
3550:- **Read-only traversal** (`forEachReadOnly`): zero-allocation — yields the live stored reference even for object `T`. Caller must NOT mutate.
3551:- **Serialization** (`getState`, `Layer.fromState`, `clone`): for object `T`, values are cloned at both ends.
3552:
3553:The primitive fast-path makes `Layer<number>`, `Layer<boolean>`, `Layer<string>`, and `Layer<null>` zero-allocation across reads and writes. For object `T`, cloning every read costs O(value size) per call — if profiling shows this dominates, use `forEachReadOnly` in tight loops or batch reads via `getState()`.
3554:
3555:**Strip-at-write sparsity.** Writes that match `defaultValue` (by `===` for primitive `T`, by `jsonFingerprint` for object `T`) `delete` the underlying entry instead of storing it. `fill(defaultValue)` short-circuits to clearing the entire sparse map. The in-memory and canonical-sparse representations stay in sync without a `getState` round-trip.
3556:
3557:### Properties
3558:
3559:| Property | Type | Description |
3560:|---|---|---|
3561:| `worldWidth` | `number` | World coordinate range (read-only) |
3562:| `worldHeight` | `number` | World coordinate range (read-only) |
3563:| `blockSize` | `number` | Cell size in world units (read-only) |
3564:| `width` | `number` | Cell grid width = `ceil(worldWidth / blockSize)` |
3565:| `height` | `number` | Cell grid height = `ceil(worldHeight / blockSize)` |
3566:| `defaultValue` | `T` | Getter returning a fresh `structuredClone` of the internal default value (mutating the result does not affect the Layer) |
3567:
3568:### `getCell(cx, cy)` / `setCell(cx, cy, value)`
3569:
3570:```typescript
3571:getCell(cx: number, cy: number): T
3572:setCell(cx: number, cy: number, value: T): void
3573:```
3574:
3575:Cell-coordinate access. `cx` and `cy` must be integers in `[0, width)` × `[0, height)` — both out-of-range and non-integer inputs throw `RangeError`. `setCell` validates `value` via `assertJsonCompatible` and `structuredClone`s before storage. `getCell` `structuredClone`s before returning.
3576:
3577:### `getAt(worldX, worldY)` / `setAt(worldX, worldY, value)`
3578:
3579:```typescript
3580:getAt(worldX: number, worldY: number): T
3581:setAt(worldX: number, worldY: number, value: T): void
3582:```
3583:
3584:World-coordinate access; auto-buckets to `Math.floor(worldX / blockSize)`, `Math.floor(worldY / blockSize)`. `worldX` and `worldY` must be integers in `[0, worldWidth)` × `[0, worldHeight)` — both out-of-range and non-integer inputs throw `RangeError`. Same defensive-copy contract as `getCell` / `setCell`.
3585:
3586:### `fill(value)`
3587:
3588:```typescript
3589:fill(value: T): void
3590:```
3591:
3592:Sets every cell to `value`. Validates once via `assertJsonCompatible`, then `structuredClone`s once per cell so each cell holds an independent copy. Subsequent `getState()` strips entries that match `defaultValue` (by `jsonFingerprint`), so `fill(defaultValue)` then `getState()` produces an empty `cells` array.
3593:
3594:### `forEach(cb)`
3595:
3596:```typescript
3597:forEach(cb: (value: T, cx: number, cy: number) => void): void
3598:```
3599:
3600:Visits every cell in row-major order (`cy` outer, `cx` inner). For object `T`, each invocation receives a fresh `structuredClone` — mutating the callback's `value` argument does not affect the Layer. For primitive `T`, the value is passed directly (no clone). Unset cells yield `defaultValue` (cloned for object `T`).
3601:
3602:### `forEachReadOnly(cb)`
3603:
3604:```typescript
3605:forEachReadOnly(cb: (value: T, cx: number, cy: number) => void): void
3606:```
3607:
3608:Zero-allocation traversal. For non-default cells, yields the live stored reference. For unset cells, yields the live `_defaultValue`. **Caller must not mutate the value** — for object `T` the reference is shared with internal storage. Use `forEach` if you need a defensive copy. Use `forEachReadOnly` in hot paths where you only read.
3609:
3610:### `clear(cx, cy)` / `clearAt(worldX, worldY)`
3611:
3612:```typescript
3613:clear(cx: number, cy: number): void
3614:clearAt(worldX: number, worldY: number): void
3615:```
3616:
3617:Drops the cell back to default — deletes the underlying sparse-map entry. Idempotent on already-default cells. Bounds-validated and integer-validated the same way as `setCell` / `setAt`.
3618:
3619:### `getState()` / `Layer.fromState(state)`
3620:
3621:```typescript
3622:getState(): LayerState<T>
3623:static fromState<T>(state: LayerState<T>): Layer<T>
3624:```
3625:
3626:Round-trip serialization. `getState` strips entries that match `defaultValue` (by `jsonFingerprint`), `structuredClone`s the rest, and sorts by cell index for determinism. `Layer.fromState` validates state shape (non-null object, `cells` is an array of `[index, value]` tuples, `blockSize` is present), validates each cell index is a safe integer in `[0, width * height)`, rejects duplicates, validates each value is JSON-compatible, and **canonicalizes** by stripping any cell whose value matches `defaultValue` (so a malformed snapshot with redundant default entries normalizes on load).
3627:
3628:**Throws (fromState):**
3629:- `TypeError` if `state` is not a non-null object
3630:- `Error` if `state.blockSize` is `undefined` or `null`
3631:- `TypeError` if `state.cells` is not an array
3632:- `TypeError` if any cell entry is not a 2-element `[index, value]` tuple
3633:- `RangeError` if any cell index is not a safe integer in `[0, width * height)`
3634:- `Error` if any cell index appears more than once
3635:- `Error` if any value is not JSON-compatible
3636:
3637:Note on the fingerprint comparison: `jsonFingerprint` uses `JSON.stringify`, which serializes object keys in insertion order. Two objects that are deeply equal but constructed with different key orders will not match — for object-typed `T` defaults, write your values with the same key order as `defaultValue` if you want them to be stripped on serialize.
3638:
3639:### `clone()`
3640:
3641:```typescript
3642:clone(): Layer<T>
3643:```
3644:
3645:Returns an independent deep copy. For object `T`, every stored entry is `structuredClone`d. For primitive `T`, entries are copied by value. The implementation iterates the sparse map directly (no intermediate `getState` round-trip).
3646:
3647:### Example
3648:
3649:```typescript
3650:const pollution = new Layer<number>({
3651:  worldWidth: 64,
3652:  worldHeight: 64,
3653:  blockSize: 4, // 16 × 16 cells
3654:  defaultValue: 0,
3655:});
3656:
3657:// Factory pollutes the cell containing world coord (10, 12)
3658:pollution.setAt(10, 12, 80);
3659:
3660:// Any agent querying nearby world coords in the same 4×4 cell sees the value
3661:console.log(pollution.getAt(11, 13)); // 80
3662:console.log(pollution.getAt(8, 12));  // 80 (same cell)
3663:console.log(pollution.getAt(20, 12)); // 0  (different cell)
3664:
3665:// Snapshot for save state
3666:const snapshot = pollution.getState();
3667:const restored = Layer.fromState<number>(snapshot);
3668:```
3669:
