3671:
3672:## Noise
3673:
3674:Seedable 2D simplex noise for procedural generation. Standalone utility.
3675:
3676:```typescript
3677:import { createNoise2D, octaveNoise2D } from 'civ-engine';
3678:```
3679:
3680:### `createNoise2D(seed)`
3681:
3682:```typescript
3683:createNoise2D(seed: number): (x: number, y: number) => number
3684:```
3685:
3686:Creates a noise function from a seed. The same seed always produces the same output. Returns values in `[-1, 1]`.
3687:
3688:```typescript
3689:const noise = createNoise2D(42);
3690:const value = noise(1.5, 2.3); // number in [-1, 1]
3691:```
3692:
3693:### `octaveNoise2D(noise, x, y, octaves, persistence?, lacunarity?)`
3694:
3695:```typescript
3696:octaveNoise2D(
3697:  noise: (x: number, y: number) => number,
3698:  x: number,
3699:  y: number,
3700:  octaves: number,
3701:  persistence?: number,  // default: 0.5
3702:  lacunarity?: number,   // default: 2.0
3703:): number
3704:```
3705:
3706:Layers multiple noise samples at increasing frequency and decreasing amplitude (fractal Brownian motion). Produces more natural-looking terrain than single-octave noise. Returns values in `[-1, 1]` when the input `noise` function is bounded to `[-1, 1]`.
3707:
3708:Throws `RangeError` if `octaves < 1` or non-integer, `persistence < 0` or non-finite, or `lacunarity <= 0` or non-finite.
3709:
3710:| Parameter | Default | Description |
3711:|---|---|---|
3712:| `octaves` | (required) | Number of noise layers (positive integer) |
3713:| `persistence` | `0.5` | Amplitude multiplier per octave (lower = smoother; must be `>= 0`) |
3714:| `lacunarity` | `2.0` | Frequency multiplier per octave (higher = more detail; must be `> 0`) |
3715:
3716:```typescript
3717:const noise = createNoise2D(42);
3718:
3719:// 4 octaves for terrain generation
3720:for (let y = 0; y < 64; y++) {
3721:  for (let x = 0; x < 64; x++) {
3722:    const elevation = octaveNoise2D(noise, x * 0.05, y * 0.05, 4);
3723:    // elevation: -1 (deep water) to 1 (mountain peaks)
3724:  }
3725:}
3726:```
3727:
3728:---
3729:
3730:## Cellular Automata
3731:
3732:Immutable cellular automata for map generation. Each step produces a new grid. Standalone utility.
3733:
3734:```typescript
3735:import {
3736:  createCellGrid,
3737:  stepCellGrid,
3738:  MOORE_OFFSETS,
3739:  VON_NEUMANN_OFFSETS,
3740:  type CellGrid,
3741:  type CellRule,
3742:} from 'civ-engine';
3743:```
3744:
3745:### `createCellGrid(width, height, fill)`
3746:
3747:```typescript
3748:createCellGrid(
3749:  width: number,
3750:  height: number,
3751:  fill: (x: number, y: number) => number,
3752:): CellGrid
3753:```
3754:
3755:Creates a cell grid from a fill function. The fill function is called for every cell with its coordinates.
3756:
3757:```typescript
3758:// Random binary grid
3759:const grid = createCellGrid(32, 32, () => Math.random() > 0.5 ? 1 : 0);
3760:
3761:// Noise-seeded grid
3762:const noise = createNoise2D(42);
3763:const grid = createCellGrid(32, 32, (x, y) =>
3764:  octaveNoise2D(noise, x * 0.1, y * 0.1, 4) > 0 ? 1 : 0
3765:);
3766:```
3767:
3768:### `stepCellGrid(grid, rule, offsets?)`
3769:
3770:```typescript
3771:stepCellGrid(
3772:  grid: CellGrid,
3773:  rule: CellRule,
3774:  offsets?: ReadonlyArray<[number, number]>,  // default: MOORE_OFFSETS
3775:): CellGrid
3776:```
3777:
3778:Produces a new grid by applying the rule function to every cell. The original grid is not mutated. Out-of-bounds neighbors are excluded (edge cells have fewer neighbors).
3779:
3780:```typescript
3781:// Game of Life rule
3782:const gameOfLife: CellRule = (current, neighbors) => {
3783:  const alive = neighbors.filter(n => n === 1).length;
3784:  if (current === 1) return (alive === 2 || alive === 3) ? 1 : 0;
3785:  return alive === 3 ? 1 : 0;
3786:};
3787:
3788:let grid = createCellGrid(32, 32, () => Math.random() > 0.6 ? 1 : 0);
3789:for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
3790:  grid = stepCellGrid(grid, gameOfLife);
3791:}
3792:
3793:// Cave generation (smoothing rule)
3794:const caveSmooth: CellRule = (current, neighbors) => {
3795:  const walls = neighbors.filter(n => n === 1).length;
3796:  return walls >= 5 ? 1 : walls <= 2 ? 0 : current;
3797:};
3798:```
3799:
3800:### Neighborhood Constants
3801:
3802:| Constant | Pattern | Count | Description |
3803:|---|---|---|---|
3804:| `MOORE_OFFSETS` | 8 surrounding cells | 8 | Default. All 8 neighbors (orthogonal + diagonal) |
3805:| `VON_NEUMANN_OFFSETS` | 4 adjacent cells | 4 | Only orthogonal neighbors (up, down, left, right) |
3806:
3807:---
3808:
3809:## Map Generation
3810:
3811:Helpers for bulk tile entity creation. Standalone utility.
3812:
3813:```typescript
3814:import { createTileGrid, type MapGenerator } from 'civ-engine';
3815:```
3816:
3817:### `createTileGrid(world, positionKey?)`
3818:
3819:```typescript
3820:createTileGrid(
3821:  world: World,
3822:  positionKey?: string,  // default: 'position'
3823:): EntityId[][]
3824:```
3825:
3826:Creates one entity per grid cell and attaches a position component to each. Returns a 2D array indexed as `tiles[y][x]`.
3827:
3828:The position component must be registered on the world before calling this function.
3829:
3830:**Throws:** `Error` (via `query`) if the position component is not registered.
3831:
3832:```typescript
3833:world.registerComponent<Position>('position');
3834:const tiles = createTileGrid(world);
3835:// tiles[0][0] = entity at (0, 0)
3836:// tiles[3][5] = entity at (5, 3)
3837:
3838:// Add terrain data to tiles
3839:world.registerComponent<{ type: string }>('terrain');
3840:tiles[3][5]; // entity ID at x=5, y=3
3841:world.addComponent(tiles[3][5], 'terrain', { type: 'forest' });
3842:```
3843:
3844:### `MapGenerator` Interface
3845:
3846:```typescript
3847:interface MapGenerator {
3848:  generate(world: World, tiles: EntityId[][]): void;
3849:}
3850:```
3851:
3852:An optional interface for organizing map generation logic. Not enforced by the engine.
3853:
3854:```typescript
3855:const myGenerator: MapGenerator = {
3856:  generate(world, tiles) {
3857:    const noise = createNoise2D(42);
3858:    for (let y = 0; y < tiles.length; y++) {
3859:      for (let x = 0; x < tiles[y].length; x++) {
3860:        const value = octaveNoise2D(noise, x * 0.05, y * 0.05, 4);
3861:        const type = value > 0.3 ? 'mountain' : value > -0.2 ? 'grass' : 'water';
3862:        world.addComponent(tiles[y][x], 'terrain', { type });
3863:      }
3864:    }
3865:  },
3866:};
3867:
3868:const tiles = createTileGrid(world);
3869:myGenerator.generate(world, tiles);
3870:```
3871:
3872:---
3873:
3874:## Behavior Tree
3875:
3876:Generic behavior tree framework for AI decision-making. Trees are structural blueprints shared across entities; per-entity execution state lives in `BTState` (stored as a component). Standalone utility.
3877:
3878:```typescript
3879:import {
3880:  createBehaviorTree,
3881:  createBTState,
3882:  NodeStatus,
3883:  type BTState,
3884:  type BTNode,
3885:  type TreeBuilder,
3886:} from 'civ-engine';
3887:```
3888:
3889:### `createBehaviorTree<TContext>(getState, define)`
3890:
3891:```typescript
3892:createBehaviorTree<TContext>(
3893:  getState: (ctx: TContext) => BTState,
3894:  define: (builder: TreeBuilder<TContext>) => BTNode<TContext>,
3895:): BTNode<TContext>
3896:```
3897:
3898:Creates a behavior tree. `TContext` is game-defined — the engine does not prescribe what it contains.
3899:
3900:**Parameters:**
3901:- `getState` — Extracts the `BTState` from the context (used by composite nodes to track which child is running)
3902:- `define` — Builder function that constructs the tree using the `TreeBuilder` API
3903:
3904:**Returns:** The root `BTNode`, which has a `tick(context)` method and a `nodeCount` property.
3905:
3906:### `createBTState(tree)`
3907:
3908:```typescript
3909:createBTState(tree: BTNode<unknown>): BTState
3910:```
3911:
3912:Creates a fresh `BTState` sized to the given tree. All running indices start at `-1` (no child running).
3913:
3914:### Builder Nodes
3915:
3916:All nodes are created through the `TreeBuilder` passed to the `define` callback:
3917:
3918:#### `builder.action(fn)`
3919:
3920:Leaf node that runs a function returning `NodeStatus`. Use for concrete actions (move, attack, gather).
3921:
3922:```typescript
3923:builder.action((ctx) => {
3924:  // do something
3925:  return NodeStatus.SUCCESS;
3926:});
3927:```
3928:
3929:#### `builder.condition(fn)`
3930:
3931:Leaf node that runs a boolean test. Returns `SUCCESS` if true, `FAILURE` if false.
3932:
3933:```typescript
3934:builder.condition((ctx) => ctx.health > 0);
3935:```
3936:
3937:#### `builder.selector(children)`
3938:
3939:Composite node that tries children left-to-right until one succeeds or returns `RUNNING`. If all fail, the selector fails. Resumes from the running child on the next tick.
3940:
3941:```typescript
3942:builder.selector([
3943:  builder.condition((ctx) => ctx.hasFood),
3944:  builder.action((ctx) => { ctx.forage(); return NodeStatus.SUCCESS; }),
3945:]);
3946:```
3947:
3948:#### `builder.sequence(children)`
3949:
3950:Composite node that runs children left-to-right until one fails or returns `RUNNING`. If all succeed, the sequence succeeds. Resumes from the running child on the next tick.
3951:
3952:```typescript
3953:builder.sequence([
3954:  builder.condition((ctx) => ctx.hasTarget),
3955:  builder.action((ctx) => ctx.moveToTarget()),
3956:  builder.action((ctx) => ctx.attack()),
3957:]);
3958:```
3959:
3960:#### `builder.reactiveSelector(children)`
3961:
3962:Like `selector`, but does not persist running state across ticks. Each tick re-evaluates children from index 0. Use when higher-priority children must pre-empt a previously running lower-priority branch (e.g., a sleep/eat need should interrupt a work branch).
3963:
3964:```typescript
3965:builder.reactiveSelector([
3966:  builder.sequence([
3967:    builder.condition((ctx) => ctx.energy < 0.2),
3968:    builder.action((ctx) => ctx.sleep()),
3969:  ]),
3970:  builder.action((ctx) => ctx.work()),
3971:]);
3972:```
3973:
3974:#### `builder.reactiveSequence(children)`
3975:
3976:Like `sequence`, but does not persist running state across ticks. Each tick restarts evaluation from child 0. Use with a `condition` as the first child to get guard-then-body semantics that re-check the guard every tick.
3977:
3978:```typescript
3979:builder.reactiveSequence([
3980:  builder.condition((ctx) => ctx.hasTarget),
3981:  builder.action((ctx) => ctx.advance()),
3982:]);
3983:```
3984:
3985:#### `clearRunningState(state, node?)`
3986:
3987:```typescript
3988:clearRunningState(state: BTState, node?: BTNode<unknown>): void
3989:```
3990:
3991:Resets running indices in a `BTState`. Without `node`, resets the entire tree. With `node`, resets only the subtree rooted at `node` — useful when external events (job reassignment, loot pickup) should interrupt a currently running branch.
3992:
3993:```typescript
3994:import { clearRunningState } from 'civ-engine';
3995:// Full reset
3996:clearRunningState(entity.btState);
3997:// Subtree reset
3998:clearRunningState(entity.btState, subtreeRoot);
3999:```
4000:
4001:### Complete Example
4002:
4003:```typescript
4004:import {
4005:  World,
4006:  createBehaviorTree,
4007:  createBTState,
4008:  NodeStatus,
4009:  type BTState,
4010:  type BTNode,
4011:  type Position,
4012:  type EntityId,
4013:} from 'civ-engine';
4014:
4015:// Define game-specific context
4016:interface AIContext {
4017:  entityId: EntityId;
4018:  world: World;
4019:  btState: BTState;
4020:}
4021:
4022:// Define the behavior tree (shared across all entities)
4023:const tree: BTNode<AIContext> = createBehaviorTree<AIContext>(
4024:  (ctx) => ctx.btState,
4025:  (b) =>
4026:    b.selector([
4027:      // Priority 1: flee if low health
4028:      b.sequence([
4029:        b.condition((ctx) => {
4030:          const hp = ctx.world.getComponent<{ hp: number }>(ctx.entityId, 'health');
4031:          return hp !== undefined && hp.hp < 20;
4032:        }),
4033:        b.action((ctx) => {
4034:          // flee logic
4035:          return NodeStatus.SUCCESS;
4036:        }),
4037:      ]),
4038:      // Priority 2: attack nearby enemy
4039:      b.sequence([
4040:        b.condition((ctx) => {
4041:          const pos = ctx.world.getComponent<Position>(ctx.entityId, 'position')!;
4042:          const nearby = ctx.world.grid.getNeighbors(pos.x, pos.y);
4043:          return nearby.length > 0;
4044:        }),
4045:        b.action((ctx) => {
4046:          // attack logic
4047:          return NodeStatus.SUCCESS;
4048:        }),
4049:      ]),
4050:      // Priority 3: wander
4051:      b.action((ctx) => {
4052:        // wander logic
4053:        return NodeStatus.SUCCESS;
4054:      }),
4055:    ]),
4056:);
4057:
4058:// Store BTState as a component
4059:world.registerComponent<BTState>('btState');
4060:
4061:// Create an entity with AI
4062:const unit = world.createEntity();
4063:world.addComponent(unit, 'btState', createBTState(tree));
4064:
4065:// System that ticks behavior trees
4066:function aiSystem(w: World): void {
4067:  for (const id of w.query('btState', 'position')) {
4068:    const btState = w.getComponent<BTState>(id, 'btState')!;
4069:    const ctx: AIContext = { entityId: id, world: w, btState };
4070:    tree.tick(ctx);
4071:  }
4072:}
4073:
4074:world.registerSystem(aiSystem);
4075:```
4076:
4077:---
4078:
4079:## Client Adapter
4080:
4081:Transport-agnostic bridge between the World and external clients. The adapter serializes world state into typed messages and dispatches incoming commands. Standalone class that uses only World's public API.
4082:
4083:```typescript
4084:import {
4085:  ClientAdapter,
4086:  type ServerMessage,
4087:  type ClientMessage,
4088:  type GameEvent,
4089:} from 'civ-engine';
4090:```
4091:
4092:### Constructor
4093:
4094:```typescript
4095:new ClientAdapter<TEventMap, TCommandMap>(config: {
4096:  world: World<TEventMap, TCommandMap>;
4097:  send: (message: ServerMessage<TEventMap>) => void;
4098:  onError?: (error: unknown) => void;
4099:})
4100:```
4101:
4102:| Parameter | Description |
4103:|---|---|
4104:| `world` | The World instance to bridge |
4105:| `send` | Callback invoked for every outgoing server message |
4106:| `onError` | Optional callback invoked when `send` throws; the adapter disconnects after reporting |
4107:
4108:### Methods
4109:
4110:#### `connect()`
4111:
4112:```typescript
4113:connect(): void
4114:```
4115:
4116:Starts streaming. Immediately sends a `snapshot` message with the full world state, then subscribes to diffs, command execution results, and tick failures. No-op if already connected.
4117:
4118:#### `disconnect()`
4119:
4120:```typescript
4121:disconnect(): void
4122:```
4123:
4124:Stops streaming. Unsubscribes from diffs. No-op if already disconnected.
4125:
4126:#### `handleMessage(message)`
4127:
4128:```typescript
4129:handleMessage(message: ClientMessage<TCommandMap> | unknown): void
4130:```
4131:
4132:Processes an incoming client message:
4133:
4134:| Message type | Behavior |
4135:|---|---|
4136:| `command` | Validates the envelope, rejects unhandled command types, then calls `world.submitWithResult()`. Sends `commandAccepted` on success or `commandRejected` with structured error fields on failure. If the command was queued, later streams `commandExecuted` or `commandFailed` after tick processing |
4137:| `requestSnapshot` | Sends a `snapshot` message with the current world state |
4138:
4139:Malformed messages without a usable `type` are ignored. Malformed command envelopes with an ID are rejected when the adapter can safely identify which command to reject.
4140:
4141:### WebSocket Example
4142:
4143:```typescript
4144:import { WebSocketServer } from 'ws';
4145:
4146:const wss = new WebSocketServer({ port: 8080 });
4147:
4148:wss.on('connection', (ws) => {
4149:  const adapter = new ClientAdapter({
4150:    world,
4151:    send: (msg) => ws.send(JSON.stringify(msg)),
4152:  });
4153:
4154:  ws.on('message', (data) => {
4155:    adapter.handleMessage(JSON.parse(data.toString()));
4156:  });
4157:
4158:  ws.on('close', () => adapter.disconnect());
4159:
4160:  adapter.connect();
4161:});
4162:```
4163:
4164:### stdin/stdout Example (for AI agents)
4165:
4166:```typescript
4167:import * as readline from 'readline';
4168:
4169:const rl = readline.createInterface({ input: process.stdin });
4170:
4171:const adapter = new ClientAdapter({
4172:  world,
4173:  send: (msg) => {
4174:    process.stdout.write(JSON.stringify(msg) + '\n');
4175:  },
4176:});
4177:
4178:rl.on('line', (line) => {
4179:  adapter.handleMessage(JSON.parse(line));
4180:});
4181:
4182:adapter.connect();
4183:```
4184:
