1:# Synthetic Playtest Harness
2:
3:The synthetic playtest harness is a Tier-1 primitive of the AI-first feedback loop (Spec 3 of `docs/design/ai-first-dev-roadmap.md`). It drives a `World` autonomously via pluggable `Policy` functions for `N` ticks and produces a replayable `SessionBundle`.
4:
5:## Quickstart
6:
7:```typescript
8:import {
9:  World, runSynthPlaytest, randomPolicy, SessionReplayer,
10:  type WorldConfig,
11:} from 'civ-engine';
12:
13:const config: WorldConfig = { gridWidth: 32, gridHeight: 32, tps: 60, positionKey: 'position' };
14:
15:interface Cmds { spawn: { x: number; y: number } }
16:
17:const setup = () => {
18:  const w = new World<Record<string, never>, Cmds>(config);
19:  w.registerHandler('spawn', (data, world) => {
20:    const id = world.createEntity();
21:    world.setComponent(id, 'position', { x: data.x, y: data.y });
22:  });
23:  w.registerComponent('position');
24:  return w;
25:};
26:
27:const result = runSynthPlaytest({
28:  world: setup(),
29:  policies: [
30:    randomPolicy<Record<string, never>, Cmds>({
31:      catalog: [
32:        (ctx) => ({
33:          type: 'spawn',
34:          data: {
35:            x: Math.floor(ctx.random() * 32),
36:            y: Math.floor(ctx.random() * 32),
37:          },
38:        }),
39:      ],
40:      frequency: 5,
41:    }),
42:  ],
43:  maxTicks: 1000,
44:  policySeed: 42,
45:});
46:
47:console.log(`Stopped: ${result.stopReason} after ${result.ticksRun} ticks`);
48:console.log(`Bundle has ${result.bundle.commands.length} recorded commands.`);
49:
50:// Verify replay-determinism (only meaningful for non-poisoned bundles with ticksRun >= 1).
51:if (result.ok && result.stopReason !== 'poisoned' && result.ticksRun >= 1) {
52:  const replayer = SessionReplayer.fromBundle(result.bundle, {
53:    worldFactory: (snap) => {
54:      const w = setup();
55:      w.applySnapshot(snap);
56:      return w;
57:    },
58:  });
59:  console.log('selfCheck:', replayer.selfCheck().ok);
60:}
61:```
62:
63:## Policy Authoring
64:
65:A `Policy` is a function from `PolicyContext` to an array of `PolicyCommand`s:
66:
67:```typescript
68:type Policy<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState> = (
69:  context: PolicyContext<TEventMap, TCommandMap, TComponents, TState>,
70:) => PolicyCommand<TCommandMap>[];
71:```
72:
73:`PolicyContext` exposes:
74:- `world` — read-only view of the current world.
75:- `tick` — the tick that's about to execute.
76:- `random` — seeded sub-RNG independent of `world.rng`. **Use this for any randomness; do NOT call `Math.random()`, `world.random()`, `Date.now()`, or other non-deterministic sources.**
77:
78:### Writing a custom policy
79:
80:```typescript
81:function migrateUnitsPolicy(): Policy<Record<string, never>, Cmds> {
82:  return (ctx) => {
83:    // Read live world state.
84:    const units = [...ctx.world.query('unit')];
85:
86:    // Use ctx.random for any randomness (NOT world.random).
87:    const targets = units.map((id) => ({
88:      id,
89:      to: { x: Math.floor(ctx.random() * 32), y: Math.floor(ctx.random() * 32) },
90:    }));
91:
92:    // Return commands; the harness submits them via world.submitWithResult.
93:    return targets.map((t) => ({ type: 'move', data: t }));
94:  };
95:}
96:```
97:
98:### Stateful policies
99:
100:A policy can carry state across calls via a closure or class method:
101:
102:```typescript
103:function memoryPolicy(): Policy<Record<string, never>, Cmds> {
104:  const seen = new Set<number>();
105:  return (ctx) => {
106:    const newOnes = [...ctx.world.query('unit')].filter((id) => !seen.has(id));
107:    for (const id of newOnes) seen.add(id);
108:    return newOnes.map((id) => ({ type: 'spawn', data: { parent: id } }));
109:  };
110:}
111:```
112:
113:Class-based form (per ADR 17): `instance.decide.bind(instance)` produces a `Policy` from a method.
114:
115:State must remain JSON-clean and seeded from `ctx.random()`. The harness's sub-RNG is shared by all composed policies on a tick — they consume from the same stream, so call counts matter for determinism.
116:
117:## Built-in Policies
118:
119:### `noopPolicy()`
120:
121:Submits nothing. Useful for letting world systems advance without external input (e.g., simulating AI behaviors that respond to world state without driver-injected stimulus).
122:
123:### `randomPolicy({ catalog, frequency, offset, burst })`
124:
125:Picks a random catalog entry per emit. `frequency` controls how often (every N ticks). `offset` shifts the firing pattern. `burst` controls commands per fired tick. Catalog entries receive the live `PolicyContext` so they can read world state when constructing their command. Throws `RangeError` on empty catalog or out-of-range parameters.
126:
127:### `scriptedPolicy(sequence)`
128:
129:Plays back a pre-recorded list of `{ tick, type, data }` entries. Useful for regression playback of bug bundles. Pre-grouped by tick at construction (O(1) per-tick lookup).
130:
131:### Bundle → Script Conversion
132:
133:To replay a recorded bundle's commands via `scriptedPolicy`:
134:
135:```typescript
136:const sequence = bundle.commands.map((cmd) => ({
137:  tick: cmd.submissionTick + 1,  // submissionTick is one less than executing tick
138:  type: cmd.type,
139:  data: cmd.data,
140:}));
141:const policy = scriptedPolicy(sequence);
142:```
143:
144:The `+1` is required because `RecordedCommand.submissionTick` is `world.tick` at submit time, while `ScriptedPolicyEntry.tick` is matched against `PolicyContext.tick` (the about-to-execute tick).
145:
146:## Determinism
147:
148:The harness is deterministic given identical inputs:
149:- Same world setup (components, handlers, validators, systems registered in the same order).
150:- Same policies (functions or class instances).
151:- Same `maxTicks`, `stopWhen`, `policySeed`, `snapshotInterval`.
152:- Identical engine and Node versions (per spec §11.1 clause 9).
153:
154:### Replay-determinism
155:
156:Non-poisoned synthetic bundles with `ticksRun >= 1` round-trip cleanly through `SessionReplayer.selfCheck()`. The sub-RNG sandboxes policy randomness from `world.rng`, so replay (which doesn't re-invoke policies) reproduces world state exactly.
157:
158:### Production-determinism
159:
160:Two harness runs with identical config (notably `policySeed`) produce structurally-equal bundles modulo `metadata.sessionId`, `metadata.recordedAt`, and `WorldMetrics.durationMs` (which is `performance.now()`-backed and varies between runs). Use the strip-volatile pattern when comparing:
161:
162:```typescript
163:const strip = (m: SessionMetadata) => {
164:  const copy = { ...m };
165:  delete (copy as Partial<typeof copy>).sessionId;
166:  delete (copy as Partial<typeof copy>).recordedAt;
167:  return copy;
168:};
169:expect(strip(r1.bundle.metadata)).toEqual(strip(r2.bundle.metadata));
170:```
171:
172:## Failure Modes
173:
174:| `stopReason` | Cause | `ok` | Bundle returned? |
175:|---|---|---|---|
176:| `'maxTicks'` | Loop completed N steps. | `true` | yes |
177:| `'stopWhen'` | Predicate fired post-step. | `true` | yes |
178:| `'poisoned'` | `world.step()` threw (poisoned mid-tick). | `true` | yes (with `failedTicks` populated) |
179:| `'policyError'` | Policy threw before `step()`. | `true` | yes (with `policyError` field populated; `bundle.failures` unchanged) |
180:| `'sinkError'` | Mid-tick recorder write failure. | `false` | yes (incomplete) |
181:
182:**Connect-time sink failure** (e.g., disk-full when writing initial manifest) propagates the error from `recorder.lastError` directly — no bundle returned, similar to `world-poisoned-at-start` propagation.
183:
184:**Composed-policy partial submit:** when `policies[i]` throws after `policies[0..i-1]` returned commands, the harness has already submitted those earlier commands. They appear in `bundle.commands` for the failed tick without matching executions. `selfCheck` doesn't replay across the abort point, so the orphan is benign; `result.policyError` is the authoritative diagnostic.
185:
186:## CI Pattern
187:
188:```typescript
189:import { runSynthPlaytest, SessionReplayer } from 'civ-engine';
190:
191:const result = runSynthPlaytest({ world: setup(), policies: [/* ... */], maxTicks: 1000 });
192:
193:// Bundle is always returned (except for connect-time sink failure).
194:expect(result.bundle).toBeDefined();
195:
196:// selfCheck guard: only valid for non-poisoned bundles with at least one successful step.
197:if (result.ok && result.stopReason !== 'poisoned' && result.ticksRun >= 1) {
198:  const replayer = SessionReplayer.fromBundle(result.bundle, {
199:    worldFactory: (snap) => { const w = setup(); w.applySnapshot(snap); return w; },
200:  });
201:  expect(replayer.selfCheck().ok).toBe(true);
202:}
203:```
204:
